{"title_page": "Berthold Kempinski", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Berthold Kempinski\n| image =File:J\u00fcdischer Friedhof Berlin-Wei\u00dfensee Grab Berthold Kempinski.JPG\n| caption = Kempinski's grave at [[Weissensee Cemetery]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1843|10|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Raszk\u00f3w|Raschkow]], [[Province of Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] (Raszk\u00f3w, Poland)\n| death_date =  {{death date and age|1910|3|14|1843|10|10| df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Berlin]], [[German Empire]]  \n|nationality       = Polish\n| spouse = Helene He\u00df (1855\u20131932)\n| children = Frieda Kempinski\n}}\n\n'''Berthold Kempinski''' (10 October 1843 \u2013 14 March 1910) was a Polish hotelier, the founder of the [[Kempinski]] hotels.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Berlin Leipziger Stra\u00dfe 25 Weinhaus Kempinski Cadiner Saal (1910).jpg|thumb|The Cadiner Saal at Kempinski's, Berlin]]\n[[File:Berlin Leipziger Stra\u00dfe 25 Weinhaus Kempinski.jpg|thumb|Interior of Weinhaus Kempinski]]\n\nKempinski was born in [[Raszk\u00f3w|Raschkow]], [[Province of Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] (Raszk\u00f3w, Poland), he became a travelling salesman in winetrade in his homeregion. Kempinski and his younger brother operated a wine tavern at the  [[Market Square, Wroc\u0142aw|Ring]] (Market Square) of  [[Breslau]] (Wroc\u0142aw).  In 1872 he moved to [[Berlin]] and started a small premise at Kronenstra\u00dfe and soon after the M. Kempinski & Co. wine restaurant at [[Friedrichstra\u00dfe]] / [[Leipziger Stra\u00dfe]] junction.<ref name=NDB>{{cite web| url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz40539.html?language=de|title= Kempinski, Berthold |publisher = Deutsche Biographie| language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.kempinski.com/en/hotels/about-us/history/|title=About us|publisher=Kempinski.com|language=German }}</ref><ref name=Kleining>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=gZL5AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41&dq=berthold+kempinski&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzmOXX0_TgAhVLYlAKHUAYC3QQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=berthold%20kempinski&f=false   |title=M. Kempinski & Co \u2013 Die \"Arisierung\" eines Berliner Traditionsunternehmens |last=Kleining |first=Jochen |pages = 41 ff.| year=2008 |ISBN=978-3-8366-6194-2|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe restaurant became popular for its huge selection of wine and seasonal delicacies like [[oyster]]s and [[crayfish]]. Kempinski invented the [[table d'h\u00f4te]] for a fixed price (1,25 [[German gold mark|Mark]]) and the \"half portion\" for (0,75 Mark, later 0,85 Mark) which made [[fine dining]] affordable for the middleclass population.<ref name=NDB/>\n\nIn 1889 the Kempinki restaurant at Leipziger Stra\u00dfe 25 was opened, the largest business of its kind in Berlin. [[Wilhelm II]] selected the [[mayolica]] tiles  from his [[Kadyny|Cadiner Majolika]] manufactury and attended the opening of the Kaisersaal (Emperor's hall). Kempinsky later specialised on wine trading and devolved the management to his son in law and his nephew.<ref name=NDB/>\n\nKempinski died 14 March 1910 in Berlin and was buried in an honorary grave at the Jewish [[Wei\u00dfensee cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.jewish-cemetery-weissensee.org/sites/Grabstaetten19-32.htm| title=Rundgang Grabst\u00e4tten |publisher=F\u00f6rderverein J\u00fcdischer Friedhof Weissensee| language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.berlin.de/senuvk/resources/cgi-bin-senuvk/egab/eg.pl?fieldname=grab&search=K&Search=Suche+starten |title=Friedh\u00f6fe und Ehrengrabst\u00e4tten| publisher=berlin.de|language=German}}</ref> In an obituary the [[Berliner Tageblatt]] called him one of the most popular men of Berlin.<ref name=Kleining/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kempinski, Berthold}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Raszk\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Posen]]\n[[Category:Kempinski Hotels]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:German hoteliers]]\n[[Category:German restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Berlin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Berthold Kempinski\n| image =File:J\u00fcdischer Friedhof Berlin-Wei\u00dfensee Grab Berthold Kempinski.JPG\n| caption = Kempinski's grave at [[Weissensee Cemetery]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1843|10|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Raszk\u00f3w|Raschkow]], [[Province of Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] (Raszk\u00f3w, Poland)\n| death_date =  {{death date and age|1910|3|14|1843|10|10| df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Berlin]], [[German Empire]]  \n|nationality       = German\n| spouse = Helene He\u00df (1855\u20131932)\n| children = Frieda Kempinski\n}}\n\n'''Berthold Kempinski''' (10 October 1843 \u2013 14 March 1910) was a German hotelier, the founder of the [[Kempinski]] hotels.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Berlin Leipziger Stra\u00dfe 25 Weinhaus Kempinski Cadiner Saal (1910).jpg|thumb|The Cadiner Saal at Kempinski's, Berlin]]\n[[File:Berlin Leipziger Stra\u00dfe 25 Weinhaus Kempinski.jpg|thumb|Interior of Weinhaus Kempinski]]\n\nKempinski was born in [[Raszk\u00f3w|Raschkow]], [[Province of Posen]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] (Raszk\u00f3w, Poland), he became a travelling salesman in winetrade in his homeregion. Kempinski and his younger brother operated a wine tavern at the  [[Market Square, Wroc\u0142aw|Ring]] (Market Square) of  [[Breslau]] (Wroc\u0142aw).  In 1872 he moved to [[Berlin]] and started a small premise at Kronenstra\u00dfe and soon after the M. Kempinski & Co. wine restaurant at [[Friedrichstra\u00dfe]] / [[Leipziger Stra\u00dfe]] junction.<ref name=NDB>{{cite web| url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz40539.html?language=de|title= Kempinski, Berthold |publisher = Deutsche Biographie| language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.kempinski.com/en/hotels/about-us/history/|title=About us|publisher=Kempinski.com|language=German }}</ref><ref name=Kleining>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=gZL5AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA41&dq=berthold+kempinski&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzmOXX0_TgAhVLYlAKHUAYC3QQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=berthold%20kempinski&f=false   |title=M. Kempinski & Co \u2013 Die \"Arisierung\" eines Berliner Traditionsunternehmens |last=Kleining |first=Jochen |pages = 41 ff.| year=2008 |ISBN=978-3-8366-6194-2|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe restaurant became popular for its huge selection of wine and seasonal delicacies like [[oyster]]s and [[crayfish]]. Kempinski invented the [[table d'h\u00f4te]] for a fixed price (1,25 [[German gold mark|Mark]]) and the \"half portion\" for (0,75 Mark, later 0,85 Mark) which made [[fine dining]] affordable for the middleclass population.<ref name=NDB/>\n\nIn 1889 the Kempinki restaurant at Leipziger Stra\u00dfe 25 was opened, the largest business of its kind in Berlin. [[Wilhelm II]] selected the [[mayolica]] tiles  from his [[Kadyny|Cadiner Majolika]] manufactury and attended the opening of the Kaisersaal (Emperor's hall). Kempinsky later specialised on wine trading and devolved the management to his son in law and his nephew.<ref name=NDB/>\n\nKempinski died 14 March 1910 in Berlin and was buried in an honorary grave at the Jewish [[Wei\u00dfensee cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.jewish-cemetery-weissensee.org/sites/Grabstaetten19-32.htm| title=Rundgang Grabst\u00e4tten |publisher=F\u00f6rderverein J\u00fcdischer Friedhof Weissensee| language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.berlin.de/senuvk/resources/cgi-bin-senuvk/egab/eg.pl?fieldname=grab&search=K&Search=Suche+starten |title=Friedh\u00f6fe und Ehrengrabst\u00e4tten| publisher=berlin.de|language=German}}</ref> In an obituary the [[Berliner Tageblatt]] called him one of the most popular men of Berlin.<ref name=Kleining/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kempinski, Berthold}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Raszk\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Posen]]\n[[Category:Kempinski Hotels]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:German hoteliers]]\n[[Category:German restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Berlin]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:cb14:8153:f300:4500:48da:5afc:b576", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berthold_Kempinski"}
{"title_page": "Hermann Souchon", "text_new": "'''Hermann Wilhelm Souchon''' ({{IPA-de|su\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u014b}}; 2 January 1895<ref name=lbw/> \u2013 1982) was a German Naval officer and hero who, according to the testimonies of two accomplices, executed [[Rosa Luxemburg]] on 15 January 1919 in [[Berlin]].\n\n== Biography ==\nSouchon, a nephew of Admiral [[Wilhelm Souchon]], was born in [[Bromberg]], [[Province of Posen]] (Bydgoscz, Poland).<ref name=lbw>{{cite web|url=http://www.landesarchiv-bw.de/plink/?f=2-1272609|title=Landesarchiv Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg, Abt. Staatsarchiv Ludwigsburg - Findbuch EL 902/5: Spruchkammer 9 - Crailsheim: Verfahrensakten - Strukturansicht|author=Dr. Thomas Fricke|language=German}}</ref> He served in the [[First World War]] as lieutenant in an artillery regiment. In 1915, he went to the [[Kaiserliche Marine|Imperial Navy]] as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]]. After the end of the war, he was discharged and became a member of [[Marinebrigade Ehrhardt]]. This [[Freikorps]]  was active in Berlin in January 1919, as part of the ''Garde-Kavallerie-Sch\u00fctzen-Division'' under General Lieutenant Heinrich von Hofmann.\n\nOn 15 January 1919 Rosa Luxemburg and [[Karl Liebknecht]] were captured at [[Berlin-Wilmersdorf]] by the Garde-Kavallerie-Sch\u00fctzendivision and brought to their headquarters at Hotel Eden. Captain [[Waldemar Pabst]], along with [[Horst von Pflugk-Harttung]] questioned them and gave the order to execute them. When they were being transported, Souchon jumped onto the car. He shot Luxemburg in the head after Otto Runge had knocked her down with a rifle butt.\n\nIn 1920, he flew to [[Finland]] where he worked as a bank clerk.\n\nAfter [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] had granted amnesty to those involved in the murders of Liebknecht and Luxemburg, Souchon returned to Germany in 1935 and joined the [[Luftwaffe]], where he rose to the rank of colonel (''[[Oberst]]'') during the war.  After the war he lived in [[Bad Godesberg]].\n\nWhen a documentary report on the Liebknecht-Luxemburg story was first shown in 1969 on German television [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]], Souchon with his lawyer [[Otto Kranzb\u00fchler]] sued the broadcaster, which had to retract their statement of Souchon's guilt in February 1970. Since the 1980s, the documentary has been shown again a few times and is now publicly available.<ref>''Der Fall Liebknecht-Luxemburg. Eine Semidokumentation von Dieter Ertel und Gustav Str\u00fcbel. Fernsehspiel f\u00fcr das Deutsche Fernsehen vom SDR / SWR.'' Documentary by [[S\u00fcddeutscher Rundfunk]] and [[S\u00fcdwestrundfunk]]</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Elisabeth Hannover-Dr\u00fcck, Heinrich Hannover: ''Der Mord an Rosa Luxemburg und Karl Liebknecht.'' Suhrkamp, Frankfurt 1967.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.geo.de/GEO/kultur/geschichte/54920.html?t=print ''Die M\u00f6rder Rosa Luxemburgs'']. In: Geo Epoche, Nr. 27,  August 2007\n* [http://www.hamburger-fortbildungstage.de/2008/Der_Feind_im_Inneren.html [[Wolfram Wette]]: ''Der Feind im Inneren'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Souchon, Hermann}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bydgoszcz]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Posen]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:German assassins]]\n[[Category:20th-century Freikorps personnel]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hermann Wilhelm Souchon''' ({{IPA-de|su\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u014b}}; 2 January 1895<ref name=lbw/> \u2013 1982) was a German Naval officer who, according to the testimonies of two accomplices, executed [[Rosa Luxemburg]] on 15 January 1919 in [[Berlin]].\n\n== Biography ==\nSouchon, a nephew of Admiral [[Wilhelm Souchon]], was born in [[Bromberg]], [[Province of Posen]] (Bydgoscz, Poland).<ref name=lbw>{{cite web|url=http://www.landesarchiv-bw.de/plink/?f=2-1272609|title=Landesarchiv Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg, Abt. Staatsarchiv Ludwigsburg - Findbuch EL 902/5: Spruchkammer 9 - Crailsheim: Verfahrensakten - Strukturansicht|author=Dr. Thomas Fricke|language=German}}</ref> He served in the [[First World War]] as lieutenant in an artillery regiment. In 1915, he went to the [[Kaiserliche Marine|Imperial Navy]] as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]]. After the end of the war, he was discharged and became a member of [[Marinebrigade Ehrhardt]]. This [[Freikorps]]  was active in Berlin in January 1919, as part of the ''Garde-Kavallerie-Sch\u00fctzen-Division'' under General Lieutenant Heinrich von Hofmann.\n\nOn 15 January 1919 Rosa Luxemburg and [[Karl Liebknecht]] were captured at [[Berlin-Wilmersdorf]] by the Garde-Kavallerie-Sch\u00fctzendivision and brought to their headquarters at Hotel Eden. Captain [[Waldemar Pabst]], along with [[Horst von Pflugk-Harttung]] questioned them and gave the order to execute them. When they were being transported, Souchon jumped onto the car. He shot Luxemburg in the head after Otto Runge had knocked her down with a rifle butt.\n\nIn 1920, he flew to [[Finland]] where he worked as a bank clerk.\n\nAfter [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] had granted amnesty to those involved in the murders of Liebknecht and Luxemburg, Souchon returned to Germany in 1935 and joined the [[Luftwaffe]], where he rose to the rank of colonel (''[[Oberst]]'') during the war.  After the war he lived in [[Bad Godesberg]].\n\nWhen a documentary report on the Liebknecht-Luxemburg story was first shown in 1969 on German television [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]], Souchon with his lawyer [[Otto Kranzb\u00fchler]] sued the broadcaster, which had to retract their statement of Souchon's guilt in February 1970. Since the 1980s, the documentary has been shown again a few times and is now publicly available.<ref>''Der Fall Liebknecht-Luxemburg. Eine Semidokumentation von Dieter Ertel und Gustav Str\u00fcbel. Fernsehspiel f\u00fcr das Deutsche Fernsehen vom SDR / SWR.'' Documentary by [[S\u00fcddeutscher Rundfunk]] and [[S\u00fcdwestrundfunk]]</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Elisabeth Hannover-Dr\u00fcck, Heinrich Hannover: ''Der Mord an Rosa Luxemburg und Karl Liebknecht.'' Suhrkamp, Frankfurt 1967.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.geo.de/GEO/kultur/geschichte/54920.html?t=print ''Die M\u00f6rder Rosa Luxemburgs'']. In: Geo Epoche, Nr. 27,  August 2007\n* [http://www.hamburger-fortbildungstage.de/2008/Der_Feind_im_Inneren.html [[Wolfram Wette]]: ''Der Feind im Inneren'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Souchon, Hermann}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bydgoszcz]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Posen]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:German assassins]]\n[[Category:20th-century Freikorps personnel]]\n", "name_user": "ZhangWeiChina", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added hero. He helped save Germany from Communism.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Souchon"}
{"title_page": "Special Forces Support Group", "text_new": "{{Coord|51|24.331|N|3|27.123|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Special Forces Support Group\n| image = Insigne du Special Forces Support Group (SFSG).svg\n| image_size= 180px\n| caption = [[DZ Flash|Drop-zone flash]] worn by SFSG operators.<ref name=\"Neville, Leigh 2016\">Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.60-61</ref>\n| dates = 3 April 2006 \u2013 present<ref name=hansard/><ref>{{cite news|title=Elite special forces unit set up|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/4928028.stm|accessdate=13 January 2017|work=BBC|date=20 April 2006}}</ref>\n| country = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| type = Special operations\n| branch = Tri-service\n| role = [[Special operations|Special operations support]]<br /> [[Counter-terrorism]]\n| command_structure = [[United Kingdom Special Forces|United Kingdom Special Forces (UKSF)]]\n| garrison = [[MOD St Athan]], [[Wales]], [[United Kingdom]]<ref name=hansard/>\n| size = One [[battalion]]\n| current_commander = \n| identification_symbol = \n| identification_symbol_label = \n| battles = {{unbulleted list|[[War on Terror]]<br/>{{*}}[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>{{*}}[[Iraq War]]}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Special Forces Support Group''' ('''SFSG''') is a unit of the [[British Armed Forces]]. The SFSG is the newest addition to the [[United Kingdom Special Forces]]. It was formed officially on 3 April 2006 to provide specialist infantry and other support to the [[Special Air Service]], the [[Special Reconnaissance Regiment]] and the [[Special Boat Service]] on operations. A tri-service unit, the major element of the SFSG is [[1st Battalion, Parachute Regiment|1st Battalion]], [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|The Parachute Regiment]] (1 PARA), reinforced with a company strength group of the [[Royal Marines]]. Specialists from the [[RAF Regiment]] also form part of the SFSG's strength. The SFSG may provide extra firepower from land or air to fulfil their mission.\n\nThe SFSG also act as the hunter force during the [[Survive, Evade, Resist, Extract|SERE]] phase of the [[United Kingdom Special Forces Selection|UKSF Selection]]; in addition, the SFSG also have a rotating company group trained in Counter Terrorism (CT) to support the on-call SAS or SBS squadrons on CT rotation.<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}}, p.6,p.56-59</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:USMC-110429-M-AN675-002.jpg|left|thumb|SFSG members in a [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion|CH-53D Sea Stallion]] during a joint UKSF/[[US Marine]] mission in [[Helmand Province]], [[Afghanistan]].<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.55</ref> 27 April 2011]]\n\nDuring the [[Iraq War]], the SFSG was part of [[Task Force 88 (anti-terrorist unit)#Task Force Black/Knight|Task Force Black/Knight]] which was composed of a rotational British SAS sabre squadron and a [[platoon]] of paratroopers from the SFSG (also known as Task Force Maroon). During the [[Basra prison incident]], a platoon of SFSG accompanied A Squadron 22 SAS to [[Basra]] to assist in recovering the two detained SAS operatives.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}},p.188,p.211</ref> Paratroopers from the SFSG supported SAS operations around [[Baghdad]] usually cordoning off areas where the SAS were carrying out their missions.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1250006961}} {{ISBN|978-1250006967}} p.190</ref> In late 2005/early 2006, the SFSG took part in [[Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis#Military action & recovery of surviving hostages|Operation Lightwater]]<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}}</ref> The SFSG platoon in Iraq supported B Squadron 22nd SAS during [[Operation Larchwood 4]], killing one terrorist when he ran out of the target building and hid under a car.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}},p.214</ref> Members of the SFSG and the SAS often wore American [[Army Combat Uniform]] (ACU) or [[Desert Camouflage Uniform]] (DCU) to blend in when operating alongside American [[Joint Special Operations Command|JSOC]] units.<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.42</ref>\n[[File:HMH-462 Supports 2-8, ATF-444 and British Soldiers in Qal'ah-ye Badam 130831-M-SA716-197.jpg|thumb|An SFSG member and a US Marine disembarking from a CH-53 Sea Stallion after a joint operation in Helmand Province<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.58-59</ref> 31 August 2013]]\n\nAn SFSG company was deployed to Afghanistan in 2006 to support the SBS and SRR as part of Operation Kindle, the UKSF deployment to Afghanistan (known as Task Force 42).<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.49</ref> On 9 September 2009, the Special Boat Service, supported by the SFSG, conducted a mission to rescue [[Stephen Farrell (journalist)|Stephen Farrell]]; a journalist captured and held at a [[Taliban]] safehouse in [[Char Dara District]], [[Kunduz Province]], by Taliban insurgents. The UKSF team was inserted by helicopters from the [[160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne)|160th SOAR]], the SBS assaulted the safehouse whilst the SFSG set up a cordon. Farrell was rescued and a number of Taliban were killed, however one member of the SFSG was killed as well as Farrell's Afghan interpreter and two civilians.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1472807908}},p.243</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/09/british-soldier-killed-afghanistan|title=British soldier killed during rescue of kidnapped journalist in Afghanistan |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 September 2009 |last=Walsh |first=Declan |author-link=Declan Walsh (journalist)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |accessdate=8 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |title=Army anger as soldier killed saving journalist who ignored Taliban warning |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/6163453/Army-anger-as-soldier-killed-saving-journalist-who-ignored-Taliban-warning.html |first=Andrew |last=Pierce |date=9 September 2009 |author-link=Andrew Pierce}}</ref> Between 18\u201329 December 2009, a company from the SFSG mentored two patrols from Afghan Task Force (ATF) 444-the Afghan special operations group for Helmand Province-during Operation Tor Shpa'h.<ref>Farrell, Theo, ''Unwinnable: Britain\u2019s War in Afghanistan, 2001\u20132014'', Bodley Head, 2017 {{ISBN|1847923461|978-1847923462}}, P.298</ref>\n\nThe SFSG have been known to carry out operations in [[Helmand Province]] with the [[United States Marine Corps]]; they also often conduct unilateral raids (similar to the [[United States Army Rangers|US Army Rangers]]), but typically act as both blocking and [[quick reaction force]]s for 'Tier 1' units.<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}}p.55-56</ref> In August 2013, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that the SFSG, worked hand-in-hand with an elite unit of [[Afghan National Army Commando Corps|Afghan commandos]], known as Task Force 444, throughout Helmand Province. The unit's A Company arrived in Afghanistan in January for a six-month tour and went on to mount relentless raids against the Taliban. The Ministry of Defence sources confirmed that the SFSG and Afghan strike forces led a series of raids on suspected Taliban bomb-makers in May after three British soldiers were killed in a roadside bomb at the end of April; the raids continued for two or three times a week afterwards. Also the unit targeted insurgent supply lines in the desert near the border with Pakistan, and Taliban bases in the centre of the province.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/10251377/Elite-forces-in-secret-raids-against-Taliban-bomb-makers.html |title=Elite forces in secret raids against Taliban bomb-makers|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 August 2013 |last=Farmer |first=Ben}}</ref> In 2014, The SFSG maintained a high operational tempo months after the official end of offensive operations by UK forces.\n\n==Formation and selection==\n[[File:Special Forces Support Group Inaugural Parade at RAF St Athan, Wales on Thursday 11th May 2006. MOD 45146159.jpg|thumb|The Special Forces Support Group Inaugural Parade at RAF St Athan on 11 May 2006]]\nThe unit's creation stems from the need to provide infantry support to the [[United Kingdom Special Forces]], which became evident after the [[Battle of Tora Bora]] during which two [[Special Boat Service]] (SBS) squadrons assaulted the [[al-Qaeda]] cave complex.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jul/05/september11.afghanistan |title=Scores killed by SAS in Afghanistan |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=5 July 2002 | location=London | date=5 July 2002 | first=Richard | last=Norton-Taylor}}</ref> Previously, this support was carried out on an [[ad hoc]] basis, with infantry units assisting special forces teams when needed.\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] does not comment on special forces matters, therefore little verifiable information exists in the public domain.<ref name=scotsman>{{Cite web|accessdate=9 March 2010|work=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |title=Special forces quitting to cash in on Iraq |url=http://www.sandline.com/hotlinks/Scotsman_Spec-forces.html}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Operation Barras]] in [[Sierra Leone]], soldiers from [[1st Battalion, The Parachute Regiment]] were deployed alongside troops from the [[Special Boat Service]] (SBS) and D Squadron SAS. This was successful, as the SAS soldiers attacked the encampment containing the hostages while the soldiers from The Parachute Regiment attacked a second encampment.<ref name=\"mod\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/SpecialForcesSupportGroupFormsInWales.htm |title=Special Forces Support Group forms in Wales |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]] |accessdate=20 April 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060424185305/http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/SpecialForcesSupportGroupFormsInWales.htm |archivedate=24 April 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2004, it was announced that a unit would be formalised for this role as part of the wider [[Delivering Security in a Changing World|future army structure]]. It was initially conceived as a [[battalion]] of \"Rangers\", similar to the [[United States Army Rangers]].<ref name=Telegraph2005>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1488020/Britain-to-double-commitment-to-the-war-on-terror-with-SAS-Lite.html|title=Britain to double commitment to the war on terror with 'SAS Lite'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 April 2005 |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> The SFSG's formation was announced officially by the then [[Secretary of State for Defence]] [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]] in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] on 20 April 2006.<ref name=hansard>{{Cite web|accessdate=26 March 2010|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]|title=Special Forces Support Group|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060420/wmstext/60420m01.htm}}</ref> It was established to support British special forces units in battle overseas and on domestic \"[[counter-terrorist]]\" operations.<ref name=\"mod\" /> Most unit personnel are [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]] soldiers, [[Royal Marine]] or Army [[commando]]s, or [[RAF Regiment]] gunners.  All infantrymen selected for the SFSG have passed either the [[P company|P Company]] selection course run by the Parachute Regiment, the [[All Arms Commando Course|Royal Marines Commando course]] or the RAF Regiment Pre-Parachute selection course.<ref name=\"jdw\" /> Royal Marines and RAF Regiment gunners are sourced from across their respective Corps.<ref name=\"jdw\">{{cite journal |journal=Jane's Defence Weekly |volume=46 |issue=8 |date=25 February 2009|page=24|title=Special Effects:UK SF unit comes into its own|author=Tim Ripley}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n* '''Special Forces Support Group'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eliteukforces.info/sfsg/|title=Special Forces Support Group - SFSG|publisher=Elite UK Forces|accessdate=13 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bootcampmilitaryfitnessinstitute.com/elite-special-forces/uk-elite-special-forces/sfsg-special-forces-support-group/|title=SFSG: Special Forces Support Group|publisher=Boot Camp & Military Fitness Institute|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n**'''HQ'''\n**'''PJHQ - SSOps Team'''\n** '''D (HQ) Company'''\n*** Regimental Administration Office\n*** Quartermasters\n*** Regiment Aid Post\n*** Catering Platoon\n*** Motor Transport Platoon\n*** Operational Readiness Wing\n**** General Training Cell\n**** Counter Terrorism Cell\n**** Campaigns Training Cell\n**** Contingency Cell\n** '''A Company'''\n** '''B Company'''\n** '''C Company'''\n** '''F Company'''\n** '''G Company'''\n*** Fire Support Group 1\n*** Fire Support Group 2\n*** Fire Support Group 3\n*** Fire Support Group 4\n*** Sniper Platoon\n** '''Support Company'''\n*** Signals Platoon\n*** Mortar Platoon\n*** Patrol platoon<ref name=\"jdw\" />\n*** Joint Tactical Air Controllers (from [[RAF Regiment]])\n\nThe [[Royal Marines]] elements comprise approximately one [[platoon]] strength within each of A, B, and C Companies. The [[RAF Regiment]] also provide a [[platoon]] in B company and [[forward air controller]]s to direct [[close air support]]. The Support company comprises mortar, sniper, and patrol platoons.<ref name=\"jdw\" /> The Patrol platoon operates vehicles, including the [[Jackal (MWMIK)|Jackal]].\n\nThere is also a RAF Regiment [[CBRN]] unit assigned to the SFSG to provide specialised knowledge and capability to military and civilian agencies in detection and handling of chemical, biological, and radiological/nuclear weapons and materials.<ref name=\"jdw\" />\n\n==Uniform distinctions==\nMembers of the SFSG wear the cap badge and beret of their parent unit, however the unit's [[DZ Flash]]-a lightning bolt superimposed on a downwards pointing Excalibur-is worn on the right-hand sleeve.<ref name=\"Neville, Leigh 2016\"/><ref>Heyman, Charles, ''The Armed Forces of the United Kingdom 2014-2015'', Pen & Sword Military, 2014 {{ISBN|1783463511}} {{ISBN| 978-1783463510}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |last=Ryan |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Ryan |year=2009 |title=Fight to Win: Deadly Skills of the Elite Forces |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1846056667/#reader_1846056667 |location=London |publisher=Century |isbn=978-1-84605-666-6 |oclc=390809569}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Special Forces Support Group}}\n\n{{United Kingdom Special Forces}}\n{{British Airborne Forces}}\n{{British Commando Forces}}\n\n[[Category:British Commandos]]\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Regiments of the British Army]]\n[[Category:Special forces of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|51|24.331|N|3|27.123|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Special Forces Support Group\n| image = Insigne du Special Forces Support Group (SFSG).svg\n| image_size= 180px\n| caption = [[DZ Flash|Drop-zone flash]] worn by SFSG operators.<ref name=\"Neville, Leigh 2016\">Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.60-61</ref>\n| dates = 3 April 2006 \u2013 present<ref name=hansard/><ref>{{cite news|title=Elite special forces unit set up|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/4928028.stm|accessdate=13 January 2017|work=BBC|date=20 April 2006}}</ref>\n| country = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| type = Special operations\n| branch = Tri-service\n| role = [[Special operations|Special operations support]]<br /> [[Counter-terrorism]]\n| command_structure = [[United Kingdom Special Forces|United Kingdom Special Forces (UKSF)]]\n| garrison = [[MOD St Athan]], [[Wales]], [[United Kingdom]]<ref name=hansard/>\n| size = One [[battalion]]\n| current_commander = \n| identification_symbol = \n| identification_symbol_label = \n| battles = {{unbulleted list|[[War on Terror]]<br/>{{*}}[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>{{*}}[[Iraq War]]}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Special Forces Support Group''' ('''SFSG''') is a unit of the [[British Armed Forces]]. The SFSG is the newest addition to the [[United Kingdom Special Forces]]. It was formed officially on 3 April 2006 to provide specialist infantry and other support to the [[Special Air Service]], the [[Special Reconnaissance Regiment]] and the [[Special Boat Service]] on operations. The [[1st Battalion, Parachute Regiment|1st Battalion Parachute Regiment]] (1 PARA), a company strength group of [[Royal Marines]]. The SFSG may provide extra firepower from land or air to fulfil their mission.\n\nThe SFSG also act as the hunter force during the [[Survive, Evade, Resist, Extract|SERE]] phase of the [[United Kingdom Special Forces Selection|UKSF Selection]]; in addition, the SFSG also have a rotating company group trained in Counter Terrorism (CT) to support the on-call SAS or SBS squadrons on CT rotation.<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}}, p.6,p.56-59</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:USMC-110429-M-AN675-002.jpg|left|thumb|SFSG members in a [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion|CH-53D Sea Stallion]] during a joint UKSF/[[US Marine]] mission in [[Helmand Province]], [[Afghanistan]].<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.55</ref> 27 April 2011]]\n\nDuring the [[Iraq War]], the SFSG was part of [[Task Force 88 (anti-terrorist unit)#Task Force Black/Knight|Task Force Black/Knight]] which was composed of a rotational British SAS sabre squadron and a [[platoon]] of paratroopers from the SFSG (also known as Task Force Maroon). During the [[Basra prison incident]], a platoon of SFSG accompanied A Squadron 22 SAS to [[Basra]] to assist in recovering the two detained SAS operatives.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}},p.188,p.211</ref> Paratroopers from the SFSG supported SAS operations around [[Baghdad]] usually cordoning off areas where the SAS were carrying out their missions.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1250006961}} {{ISBN|978-1250006967}} p.190</ref> In late 2005/early 2006, the SFSG took part in [[Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis#Military action & recovery of surviving hostages|Operation Lightwater]]<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}}</ref> The SFSG platoon in Iraq supported B Squadron 22nd SAS during [[Operation Larchwood 4]], killing one terrorist when he ran out of the target building and hid under a car.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}},p.214</ref> Members of the SFSG and the SAS often wore American [[Army Combat Uniform]] (ACU) or [[Desert Camouflage Uniform]] (DCU) to blend in when operating alongside American [[Joint Special Operations Command|JSOC]] units.<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.42</ref>\n[[File:HMH-462 Supports 2-8, ATF-444 and British Soldiers in Qal'ah-ye Badam 130831-M-SA716-197.jpg|thumb|An SFSG member and a US Marine disembarking from a CH-53 Sea Stallion after a joint operation in Helmand Province<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.58-59</ref> 31 August 2013]]\n\nAn SFSG company was deployed to Afghanistan in 2006 to support the SBS and SRR as part of Operation Kindle, the UKSF deployment to Afghanistan (known as Task Force 42).<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}},p.49</ref> On 9 September 2009, the Special Boat Service, supported by the SFSG, conducted a mission to rescue [[Stephen Farrell (journalist)|Stephen Farrell]]; a journalist captured and held at a [[Taliban]] safehouse in [[Char Dara District]], [[Kunduz Province]], by Taliban insurgents. The UKSF team was inserted by helicopters from the [[160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne)|160th SOAR]], the SBS assaulted the safehouse whilst the SFSG set up a cordon. Farrell was rescued and a number of Taliban were killed, however one member of the SFSG was killed as well as Farrell's Afghan interpreter and two civilians.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1472807908}},p.243</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/09/british-soldier-killed-afghanistan|title=British soldier killed during rescue of kidnapped journalist in Afghanistan |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 September 2009 |last=Walsh |first=Declan |author-link=Declan Walsh (journalist)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |accessdate=8 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |title=Army anger as soldier killed saving journalist who ignored Taliban warning |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/6163453/Army-anger-as-soldier-killed-saving-journalist-who-ignored-Taliban-warning.html |first=Andrew |last=Pierce |date=9 September 2009 |author-link=Andrew Pierce}}</ref> Between 18\u201329 December 2009, a company from the SFSG mentored two patrols from Afghan Task Force (ATF) 444-the Afghan special operations group for Helmand Province-during Operation Tor Shpa'h.<ref>Farrell, Theo, ''Unwinnable: Britain\u2019s War in Afghanistan, 2001\u20132014'', Bodley Head, 2017 {{ISBN|1847923461|978-1847923462}}, P.298</ref>\n\nThe SFSG have been known to carry out operations in [[Helmand Province]] with the [[United States Marine Corps]]; they also often conduct unilateral raids (similar to the [[United States Army Rangers|US Army Rangers]]), but typically act as both blocking and [[quick reaction force]]s for 'Tier 1' units.<ref>Neville, Leigh, ''The SAS 1983-2014 (Elite)'', Osprey Publishing, 2016, {{ISBN|1472814037}} {{ISBN|978-1472814036}}p.55-56</ref> In August 2013, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that the SFSG, worked hand-in-hand with an elite unit of [[Afghan National Army Commando Corps|Afghan commandos]], known as Task Force 444, throughout Helmand Province. The unit's A Company arrived in Afghanistan in January for a six-month tour and went on to mount relentless raids against the Taliban. The Ministry of Defence sources confirmed that the SFSG and Afghan strike forces led a series of raids on suspected Taliban bomb-makers in May after three British soldiers were killed in a roadside bomb at the end of April; the raids continued for two or three times a week afterwards. Also the unit targeted insurgent supply lines in the desert near the border with Pakistan, and Taliban bases in the centre of the province.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/10251377/Elite-forces-in-secret-raids-against-Taliban-bomb-makers.html |title=Elite forces in secret raids against Taliban bomb-makers|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 August 2013 |last=Farmer |first=Ben}}</ref> In 2014, The SFSG maintained a high operational tempo months after the official end of offensive operations by UK forces.\n\n==Formation and selection==\n[[File:Special Forces Support Group Inaugural Parade at RAF St Athan, Wales on Thursday 11th May 2006. MOD 45146159.jpg|thumb|The Special Forces Support Group Inaugural Parade at RAF St Athan on 11 May 2006]]\nThe unit's creation stems from the need to provide infantry support to the [[United Kingdom Special Forces]], which became evident after the [[Battle of Tora Bora]] during which two [[Special Boat Service]] (SBS) squadrons assaulted the [[al-Qaeda]] cave complex.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jul/05/september11.afghanistan |title=Scores killed by SAS in Afghanistan |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=5 July 2002 | location=London | date=5 July 2002 | first=Richard | last=Norton-Taylor}}</ref> Previously, this support was carried out on an [[ad hoc]] basis, with infantry units assisting special forces teams when needed.\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] does not comment on special forces matters, therefore little verifiable information exists in the public domain.<ref name=scotsman>{{Cite web|accessdate=9 March 2010|work=[[The Scotsman]] |location=Edinburgh |title=Special forces quitting to cash in on Iraq |url=http://www.sandline.com/hotlinks/Scotsman_Spec-forces.html}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Operation Barras]] in [[Sierra Leone]], soldiers from [[1st Battalion, The Parachute Regiment]] were deployed alongside troops from the [[Special Boat Service]] (SBS) and D Squadron SAS. This was successful, as the SAS soldiers attacked the encampment containing the hostages while the soldiers from The Parachute Regiment attacked a second encampment.<ref name=\"mod\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/SpecialForcesSupportGroupFormsInWales.htm |title=Special Forces Support Group forms in Wales |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]] |accessdate=20 April 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060424185305/http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/SpecialForcesSupportGroupFormsInWales.htm |archivedate=24 April 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2004, it was announced that a unit would be formalised for this role as part of the wider [[Delivering Security in a Changing World|future army structure]]. It was initially conceived as a [[battalion]] of \"Rangers\", similar to the [[United States Army Rangers]].<ref name=Telegraph2005>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1488020/Britain-to-double-commitment-to-the-war-on-terror-with-SAS-Lite.html|title=Britain to double commitment to the war on terror with 'SAS Lite'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 April 2005 |accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref> The SFSG's formation was announced officially by the then [[Secretary of State for Defence]] [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]] in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] on 20 April 2006.<ref name=hansard>{{Cite web|accessdate=26 March 2010|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]|title=Special Forces Support Group|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060420/wmstext/60420m01.htm}}</ref> It was established to support British special forces units in battle overseas and on domestic \"[[counter-terrorist]]\" operations.<ref name=\"mod\" /> Most unit personnel are [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]] soldiers, [[Royal Marine]] or Army [[commando]]s, or [[RAF Regiment]] gunners.  All infantrymen selected for the SFSG have passed either the [[P company|P Company]] selection course run by the Parachute Regiment, the [[All Arms Commando Course|Royal Marines Commando course]] or the RAF Regiment Pre-Parachute selection course.<ref name=\"jdw\" /> Royal Marines and RAF Regiment gunners are sourced from across their respective Corps.<ref name=\"jdw\">{{cite journal |journal=Jane's Defence Weekly |volume=46 |issue=8 |date=25 February 2009|page=24|title=Special Effects:UK SF unit comes into its own|author=Tim Ripley}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n* '''Special Forces Support Group'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eliteukforces.info/sfsg/|title=Special Forces Support Group - SFSG|publisher=Elite UK Forces|accessdate=13 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bootcampmilitaryfitnessinstitute.com/elite-special-forces/uk-elite-special-forces/sfsg-special-forces-support-group/|title=SFSG: Special Forces Support Group|publisher=Boot Camp & Military Fitness Institute|accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n**'''HQ'''\n**'''PJHQ - SSOps Team'''\n** '''D (HQ) Company'''\n*** Regimental Administration Office\n*** Quartermasters\n*** Regiment Aid Post\n*** Catering Platoon\n*** Motor Transport Platoon\n*** Operational Readiness Wing\n**** General Training Cell\n**** Counter Terrorism Cell\n**** Campaigns Training Cell\n**** Contingency Cell\n** '''A Company'''\n** '''B Company'''\n** '''C Company'''\n** '''F Company'''\n** '''G Company'''\n*** Fire Support Group 1\n*** Fire Support Group 2\n*** Fire Support Group 3\n*** Fire Support Group 4\n*** Sniper Platoon\n** '''Support Company'''\n*** Signals Platoon\n*** Mortar Platoon\n*** Patrol platoon<ref name=\"jdw\" />\n*** Joint Tactical Air Controllers (from [[RAF Regiment]])\n\nThe [[Royal Marines]] elements comprise approximately one [[platoon]] strength within each of A, B, and C Companies. The [[RAF Regiment]] also provide a [[platoon]] in B company and [[forward air controller]]s to direct [[close air support]]. The Support company comprises mortar, sniper, and patrol platoons.<ref name=\"jdw\" /> The Patrol platoon operates vehicles, including the [[Jackal (MWMIK)|Jackal]].\n\nThere is also a RAF Regiment [[CBRN]] unit assigned to the SFSG to provide specialised knowledge and capability to military and civilian agencies in detection and handling of chemical, biological, and radiological/nuclear weapons and materials.<ref name=\"jdw\" />\n\n==Uniform distinctions==\nMembers of the SFSG wear the cap badge and beret of their parent unit, however the unit's [[DZ Flash]]-a lightning bolt superimposed on a downwards pointing Excalibur-is worn on the right-hand sleeve.<ref name=\"Neville, Leigh 2016\"/><ref>Heyman, Charles, ''The Armed Forces of the United Kingdom 2014-2015'', Pen & Sword Military, 2014 {{ISBN|1783463511}} {{ISBN| 978-1783463510}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |last=Ryan |first=Chris |authorlink=Chris Ryan |year=2009 |title=Fight to Win: Deadly Skills of the Elite Forces |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1846056667/#reader_1846056667 |location=London |publisher=Century |isbn=978-1-84605-666-6 |oclc=390809569}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Special Forces Support Group}}\n\n{{United Kingdom Special Forces}}\n{{British Airborne Forces}}\n{{British Commando Forces}}\n\n[[Category:British Commandos]]\n[[Category:Counter-terrorist organizations]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Regiments of the British Army]]\n[[Category:Special forces of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Hammersfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_Forces_Support_Group"}
{"title_page": "First Philippine Republic", "text_new": "{{short description|Self-proclaimed independent republic from 1899\u20131901}}\n{{Infobox country\n| native_name            = ''Rep\u00fablica Filipina''<br />''Rep\u00fablik\u00e1ng Pilipino''\n| conventional_long_name = Philippine Republic\n| common_name            = the Philippines\n| year_start             = 1899<ref name=clarifydates group=Note>The Malolos Constitution was approved by the [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|Malolos Congress]] on January 20, 1899, sanctioned by [[Emilio Aguinaldo|Aguinaldo]] on January 21, and promulgated on January 22 (see items [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/106?page=root;size=100;view=image 27] and [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/123?page=root;size=100;view=image 27a] in {{Harvnb|Guevara|1972}}). The republic was proclaimed on 23 January (see items [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/138?view=image&size=100 28], [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/139?page=root;size=100;view=image 28a] and [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/140?page=root;size=100;view=image 28b] in {{Harvnb|Guevara|1972}}).</ref>\n| year_end               = 1901\n| date_start             = January 23,\n| date_end               = March 23,\n| event_end              = Dissolved{{ref label|dissolution|''i''|none}}\n| p1                     = Spanish East Indies\n| flag_p1                = Flag of Spain (1785-1873 and 1875-1931).svg\n| p2                     = Revolutionary Government of the Philippines (1898\u20131899){{!}}Revolutionary Government\n| flag_p2                = Philippines Aguinaldo flag (obverse).svg\n| s1                     = United States Military Government of the Philippine  Islands{{!}}Military Government of the Philippine Islands\n| flag_s1                = US flag 45 stars.svg\n| image_flag             = Philippines Aguinaldo flag (obverse).svg\n| image_coat             = Emblem of the First Philippine Republic.png\n| symbol_type            = [[Coat of arms of the Philippines|Emblem]]\n| image_map              = Map of Philippines First Republic.png\n| image_map_caption      = Territory claimed by the Philippine Republic\n| national_anthem        = ''[[Lupang Hinirang|Marcha Nacional Filipina]]''<br />{{center|[[File:Himno Nacional Filipina.ogg]] }}\n| capital                = {{bulleted list\n | {{nowrap|[[Malolos]], [[Bulacan]] (''official'')}} {{nowrap|January 23, 1899<ref name=clarifydates group=Note />}} {{nowrap|to March 29, 1899}}\n | other temporary capitals<ref name=capitals group=Note>Sources disagree regarding the specific locations which were temporarily capitals of the Philippine Republic. For example:\n | {{Harvnb|Duka|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=4wk8yqCEmJUC&pg=PA191 191]}} lists a progression after Malolos from [[Cabanatuan]], [[Nueva Ecija]] to [[Tarlac City|Tarlac]] to [[Bayombong, Nueva Vizcaya]] to [[Bayambang, Pangasinan]].\n | {{Harvnb|Schultz|2000|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WDV40aK1T-sC&pg=PA322 322]}} says that the capital transferred from Malolos to [[San Fernando, Pampanga]].\n | {{Harvnb|Calit|2003|p=57}} asserts that Aguinaldo established his capital at [[San Isidro, Nueva Ecija]] after abandoning Malolos.\n | {{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=136}} does not give a comprehensive list, but notes that Aguinaldo's cabinet, reduced to a handful of ministers, moved from capital to capital.</ref>{{sup|}} }}\n| common_languages       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], and other [[Philippine languages]]\n| religion               = {{unbulleted list | [[Roman Catholicism]] | [[Philippine Independent Church]] }}\n| government_type        = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] constitutional republic\n| title_leader           = [[President of the Philippines|President]]\n| leader1                = [[Emilio Aguinaldo]]\n| year_leader1           = 1899\u20131901\n| leader2                = \n| year_leader2           = \n| title_deputy           = \n| deputy1                = \n| year_deputy1           = \n| deputy2                = \n| year_deputy2           = \n| legislature            = [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|La Asamblea Nacional]]\n| era                    = Philippine Revolution\n| area_km2           = 298,712 <ref name=NBE>[http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/results.vm?o=&w=7.832.719+habitantes.&f=text&t=%2Bcreation&l=600&l=700&s=0&lang=en La Dinast\u00eda (Barcelona). 29/11/1898, page 3.] as returned in search results at the [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es National Library of Spain].</ref>\n| stat_pop1              = 7,832,719<ref name=NBE />\n| stat_year1             = 1898\n| currency               = [[Philippine peso|Peso]]\n| footnotes              = {{Ordered list\n | list_style_type = lower-roman\n | item_style      = font-style:italic;\n | {{note label|dissolution|i|none}}For further info re-dissolution, see capture of [[Emilio Aguinaldo]].\n }}\n|status=[[List of historical unrecognized states and dependencies|Unrecognized state]]}}\n{{History of the Philippines}}\n[[File:Gen Aguinaldo.jpg|thumb|upright|First President of the Philippines, [[Emilio Aguinaldo]], in the field.]]\n[[File:Malolosrepublic.jpeg|thumb|upright=1.35|The Inauguration of the First Philippine Republic in Malolos, January 23, 1899]]\n\nThe '''Philippine Republic''' ({{lang-es|Rep\u00fablica Filipina<!-- per the official text of the 1899 constitution -->}}; {{lang-fil|Rep\u00fablik\u00e1ng Pilipino}}), more commonly known as the '''First Philippine Republic''' or the '''Malolos Republic''', was a nascent [[Philippine Revolution|revolutionary government]] in the [[Philippines]]. It was formally established with the proclamation of the [[Malolos Constitution]] on January 21, 1899, in [[Malolos]], [[Bulacan]],<ref name=clarifydates group=Note /> and endured until the capture of President [[Emilio Aguinaldo]] by the [[Military of the United States|American forces]] on March 23, 1901, in [[Palanan, Isabela|Palanan]], [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]], which effectively dissolved the First Republic.\n\nThe First Philippine Republic was established after the [[Philippine Revolution]] against the [[Spanish Empire]] (1896-1897) and the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] between Spain and the [[United States]] (1898). Following the American victory at the [[Battle of Manila Bay]], Aguinaldo returned to the Philippines, issued the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]] on June 12, 1898, and established a revolutionary Philippine government. In December 1898, Spain sold the Philippines to the United States in the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|1898 Treaty of Paris]], making the United States formally the Philippines colonial power. The Malolos Constitution establishing the First Philippine Republic was proclaimed the following month. The [[Philippine\u2013American War]] began in February 1899, which the Philippine Republic lost.\n\nThe Philippine Republic was the first constitutional republic in Asia.<ref name=guevara2005pp104-119>{{cite book\n|editor-last=Guevara|editor-first=Sulpico|title=The Laws of the First Philippine Republic (the laws of Malolos) 1898\u20131899 |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=philamer;iel=1;view=toc;idno=aab1246.0001.001\n|location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|publisher=University of Michigan Library|publication-date=1972|year=2005\n|pages=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer;cc=philamer;rgn=full%20text;idno=aab1246.0001.001;didno=aab1246.0001.001;view=image;seq=00000122 104\u2013119]|accessdate=2008-03-26|ref=harv}}. (English translation by Sulpicio Guevara)</ref> Although there were several Asian republics predating the First Philippine Republic for example, the [[Mahajanapadas]] of ancient India, the [[Lanfang Republic]], the [[Republic of Formosa]] or the [[Republic of Ezo]], the Republic at Malolos was the first to frame a comprehensive constitution duly approved by a partially elected congress.<ref name=\"tucker2009p364\">{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C. |title=The Encyclopedia of the Spanish\u2013American and Philippine\u2013American Wars: A Political, Social, and Military History|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8V3vZxOmHssC|year=2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-951-1|page=[http://books.google.com.ph/books?id=8V3vZxOmHssC&pg=RA1-PA364 364]|ref=harv}}</ref>{{fv|date=August 2019|reason=no support for either the assertion re the other listed asian republics or the assertion reading, \"the Republic at Malolos was the first to frame a comprehensive constitution duly approved by a partially elected congress\"}}\n\n==History==\nIn 1896, the Philippine Revolution began against Spanish colonial rule. In 8712\n Philippine forces led by Aguinaldo signed a ceasefire with the Spanish authorities and Aguinaldo and other leaders went into exile in Hong Kong.  In April 1898, the Spanish\u2013American War broke out.  The U.S. Navy's Asiatic Squadron, then in Hong Kong, sailed to the Philippines to engage the Spanish naval forces. On May 1, 1898, the U.S. Navy decisively defeated the Spanish Navy in the [[Battle of Manila Bay]]. Later in May, Aguinaldo returned to the Philippines, established a dictatorial government on May 24, 1898<ref name=\"423\u2013427\">{{Harvnb|Kalaw|1927|pp=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=afj2233.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=443 423\u2013427]}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Titherington|1900|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/spanishamwar00tithrich#page/357/mode/2up 357\u2013358]}}</ref> (formally established by decree on June 18<ref>{{Harvnb|Guevara|1972|pp=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=28 10\u201312]}}</ref>), and on June 12, 1898, at Aguinaldo's ancestral home in Cavite, issued the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]] from Spain.  Following the proclamation of independence Aguinaldo established a revolutionary government on June 23, 1898, under which the partly-elected and partly-appointed [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|Malolos Congress]] convened on 15 September to write a constitution.<ref name=constitution>{{Harvnb|Guevara|1972|pp=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=122&size=100 104\u2013119]}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 1898, the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|1898 Treaty of Paris]] was signed, ending the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] and transferring the Philippines from Spain to the United States.<ref name=TofP>{{citation|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/19th_century/sp1898.asp|title=Treaty of Peace Between the United States and Spain; December 10, 1898|publisher=[[Yale]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Malolos Constitution]] written by the congress was proclaimed on 22 January 1899, creating what is known today as the First Philippine Republic, with Aguinaldo as its president.<ref name=\"quod.lib.umich.edu\">{{Harvnb|Guevara|1972|p=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=122&size=100 104]}}</ref><ref name=\"423\u2013427\"/> The constitution was approved by delegates to the Malolos Congress on January 20, 1899, and sanctioned by Aguinaldo the next day.<ref name=\"quod.lib.umich.edu\"/> The convention had earlier elected Aguinaldo president on January 1, 1899, leading to his inauguration on January 23. Parts of the constitution gave Aguinaldo the power to [[rule by decree]].{{refn|The three parts of the constitution which are of particular interest are:\n:*Article 4, which lists three distinct powers, \"the legislative, the executive, and the judicial\", specifies that any two or more of these powers shall never be vested in a single individual, and specifies that the legislative power shall never be vested in a single individual.<ref name=constitution />\n:*Title VI, comprising articles 54 and 55, which mandate the election of seven legislators to a Permanent Commission which is to meet when convoked by its presiding officer during periods of legislative adjournment. This commission is mandated, among other things, \"To act on pending matters which require proper action.\"<ref name=constitution />\n:*Article 99, which read, \"Notwithstanding the general rule established in paragraph 2 of Article 4, in the meantime that the country is fighting for its independence, the Government is empowered to resolve during the closure of the Congress all questions and difficulties not provided for in the laws, which give rise to unforeseen events, by the issuance of decrees, of which the Permanent Commission shall be duly apprised as well as the Assembly when it meets in accordance with this Constitution.\"<ref name=constitution />\n:In April 1899, the Permanent Commission is said to have been composed of Pedro A. Paterno, Felix Ferrer, Juan Nepomuceno, Arsenic Cruz Herrera, Joaquin Gonzales, Hugo Ilagan, and Alberto Barretto.<ref>{{Harvnb|Zafra|1967|p=[https://books.google.com/books?ei=SkGaTpm1DO\u2013UiQeU3aSsAg&ct=result&id=g1MeAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22permanent+commission%22+philippines&q=%22Pedro+A.+Paterno%2C+Felix+Ferrer%22#search_anchor 239]}}</ref>|group=Note}}  The constitution was titled \"Constituci\u00f3n pol\u00edtica\", and was written in Spanish.<ref name=guevara2005p88>{{Harvnb|Guevara|2005|p=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=106&size=100 88]}}</ref><ref name=guevera2005p104>{{Harvnb|Guevara|2005|p=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=122&size=100 104]}}</ref><ref name=\"tucker2009pp364-365\">{{Harvnb|Tucker|2009|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8V3vZxOmHssC&pg=RA1-PA364 364\u2013365]}}</ref>\n\n===Philippine\u2013American War===\n{{main|Philippine\u2013American War}}\n\nWhen the First Philippine Republic was constituted on January 22, 1899 in Malolos, that municipality became the seat of government of the Philippine Republic, and was serving as such when hostilities erupted between U.S. and Filipino forces in the Second Battle of Manila on February 4.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=373}}</ref> On February 4, 1899, armed conflict erupted in [[Manila]] between Philippine Republic forces and American forces occupying the city subsequent to the conclusion of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]].<ref name=linn2000app46>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=46}}</ref> That day President Aguinaldo issued a proclamation ordering and commanding that \"peace and friendly relations with the Americans be broken and that the latter be treated as enemies,  within the limits prescribed by the laws of war.\"<ref>{{Harvnb|Halstead|1898|p=[http://www.gutenberg.org/catalog/world/readfile?fk_files=58428&pageno=318 318]}}</ref> The fighting quickly escalated into the [[Battle of Manila (1899)|Second Battle of Manila]], with Philippine Republic forces being driven out of the city.<ref name=linn2000app46-49>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|pp=46\u201349}}</ref>\n\nAmerican forces pushing north from Manila after the outbreak of fighting captured [[Caloocan]] on February 10.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=379\u2013381}}</ref> On March 29, as American forces threatened Malolos, the seat of government moved to San Isidro, Nueva Ecija.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=388}}</ref> On March 31, American forces captured Malolos, the initial seat of the Philippine Republic government, which had been gutted by fires set by withdrawing Philippine Republic forces.<ref name=linn2000ap99>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=99}}</ref> Emilio Aguinaldo and the core of the revolutionary government had by then moved to [[San Isidro, Nueva Ecija]].<ref name=linn2000ap109>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=109}}</ref> Peace negotiations with the American [[Schurman Commission]] during a brief ceasefire in April\u2013May 1899 failed,<ref name=linn2000ap109 /> and San Isidro fell to American forces on May 16.<ref name=linn2000p116>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=116}}.</ref> The Philippine Republic core government had moved by then to [[Bamban, Tarlac]], and subsequently moved to [[Tarlac City|Tarlac town]].<ref name=linn2000app115-116>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|pp=115\u2013116}}</ref> Aguinaldo's party had already left Tarlac, the last capital of the Philippine Republic, by the time American troops occupied it on November{{nbsp}}13.<ref name=linn2000bp16>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000b|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-5WOrmt_VxcC&pg=PA16 16]}}</ref>\n\nAmerican forces captured [[Calumpit, Bulacan]] on April 27 and, moving north, captured [[Apalit, Pampanga]] with little opposition on May 4 and [[San Fernando, Pampanga]] on May 5. This forced the seat of government to be shifted according to the demands of the military situation.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=392}}</ref><ref name=capitals group=Note />\n\nIn October 1899 American forces were in [[San Fernando, Pampanga]] and the Philippine Republic was headquartered not far north of there, in [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles]]. On October 12, an American offensive to the north forced the Philippine Republic to relocate its headquarters in November to Tarlac, and then to [[Bayombong, Nueva Vizcaya]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=446}}</ref> On November 13, under pressure by American forces, Aguinaldo and a party departed Bayombong by rail for [[Calasiao, Pangasinan]], from where they immediately proceeded eastwards to Sta. Barbara in order to evade pursuing American forces. In Sta. Barbara, they joined a force of some 1200 armed men led by General [[Gregorio del Pilar]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=447}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, in a conference in [[Bayambang, Pangasinan]], Aguinaldo decided to disperse his army and begin [[guerrilla war]]. From that point on, distance and the localistic nature of the fighting prevented him from exercising a strong influence on revolutionary or military operations.<ref name=linn2000bp16 /> Recognizing that American troops blocked his escape east, he turned north and west on 15 November, crossing the mountains into [[La Union]] province.<ref>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=148}}.</ref> Aguinaldo's party eluded pursuing American forces, passing through Tirad Pass near [[Sagada, Mountain Province]] where the [[Battle of Tirad Pass]] was fought on December 2 as a [[rear guard]] action to delay the American advance and ensure his escape. At the time of the battle, Aguinaldo and his party were encamped in [[Cervantes, Ilocos Sur|Cervantes]], about 10&nbsp;km south of the pass. After being notified by a rider of the outcome of the battle and the death of del Pilar, Aguinaldo ordered that camp be broken, and departed with his party for Cayan settlement.<ref>{{cite book|author=Teodoro A. Agoncillo|title=Malolos: The Crisis of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LnxvAAAACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=University of the Philippines Press|isbn=978-971-542-096-9|page=454}}</ref> Aguinaldo was captured by American forces on March 23, 1901 in [[Palanan, Isabela]]. Following his capture, Aguinaldo announced allegiance to the United States on April 1, 1901, formally ending the First Republic and recognizing the [[United States Military Government of the Philippine Islands|sovereignty of the United States over the Philippines]].\n\nAguinaldo's party, traveling with del Pilar's force, reached [[Manaoag, Pangasinan]] on November 15. There, the force was split into [[Vanguard (military formation)|vanguard]] and rear guard elements, with Aguinaldo and del Pilar in the vanguard.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=447\u2013448}}</ref> The vanguard force overnighted in [[Tubao, La Union]], departed there on November 16, and was in [[Naguilian, La Union]] by November 19, where word was received that American forces had taken [[Santo Tomas, La Union|Santo Tomas]] and had proceeded to [[Aringay, La Union|Aringay]]. Aguinaldo's force arrived in [[Balaoan, La Union]] on November 19, pushed on the next day, and arrived at the Tirad Pass, a natural [[choke point]], on November 23. General del Pilar decided to place a blocking force in Tirad Pass to delay pursuing American forces while Aguinaldo's party moved on.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=449}}</ref>\n\nThe Battle of Tirad Pass took place on December 2, 1899. 52 men of del Pilar's 60-man force were killed, including del Pilar himself. However, the Filipinos under del Pilar held off the Americans long enough for Aguinaldo's party to escape. Aguinaldo, encamped with his party about 10&nbsp;km south of the pass in [[Cervantes, Ilocos Sur]], was apprised of the result of the battle by a rider, and moved on. The party reached Banane settlement on December 7, where Aguinaldo paused to consider plans for the future. On December 16, the party departed for [[Abra (province)|Abra]] to join forces with General [[Manuel Tinio]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=455}}</ref> The party traveled on foot through a pass at the summit of [[Mount Polis]], and arrived at Ambayuan the next morning. The party pushed on to Banane, pursued closely by American forces. At this point, Aguinaldo's party consisted of one field officer, 11 line officers, and 107 men. The remainder of December 1899 was spent in continuous trek.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=456\u2013458}}</ref>\n\nThe party was at the border of Abra and [[Cagayan]] provinces on Aguinaldo's 31st birthday on March 23, 1900. The trek from place to place continued until about May 22, 1900, when Aguinaldo established a new headquarters in Tierra Virgen.<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 460\">{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=460}}</ref> On August 27, 1900, after American forces landed at [[Aparri, Cagayan]], Aguinaldo concluded that Tierra Virgan had become untenable as a headquarters and decided to march to [[Palanan, Isabela]].<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 460\" /> On December 6, 1900, the party reached Dumasari, and arrived in Palanan the following morning.<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 485\u2013486\">{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=485\u2013486}}</ref> Aguinaldo remained in Palanan until his capture there by American forces with the aid of the native scouts on March 23, 1901.<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 485\u2013486\" />\n\n==Organization==\n===National cabinet===\nArticle 73 of the constitution established a Council of Government (Cabinet), composed of a President and seven Secretaries. The following individuals were appointed to Cabinet positions:{{refn|Details of the composition of the cabinet differ between sources. ''Master List of Cabinet Members since 1899'' in the Philippine Government's [[Official Gazette (Philippines)|Official Gazette]] is more comprehensive than other sources seen, listing information for both the Mabini and Paterno cabinets.<ref name=guevara2005p115 />}}\n\n{{Philippine cabinet|year=1899}}\n\n===Provincial and local government===\nMunicipal and provincial governments under the Republic had quickly reorganized upon Aguinaldo's decrees of June 18 and 20, 1898.<ref name=\"malolos crisis\">{{cite book|last=Agoncillo|first=Teodoro|title=Malolos: The Crisis of the Republic|year=1960}}</ref> The [[Malolos Constitution]] cited on Article 82 the organization of provincial and popular assemblies which had the power of taxation.\n\nThe government also claimed jurisdiction over the overseas territory of Palaos (Modern day Palau) and the [[Sulu archipelago]]. Both areas are represented in the Congress by representatives appointed by President Emilio Aguinaldo. Aguinaldo sent a letter to the Sultan of Sulu requesting that the islands be part of the First Philippine Republic, but the letter was ignored.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greater Philippines: Captaincy General of the Philippines|url=http://malacanang.gov.ph/7824-evolution-of-the-revolution/|website=Presidential Museum and Library|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in 2003 that Philippine congressman [[Harry Roque]] argued that Spain could not have legally ceded Palmas or any part of the Philippines to the United States because Filipinos had already established the Republic of the Philippines on June 12, 1898 before the Treaty of Paris was signed on Dec. 10, 1898.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/193954/special-report-legal-battle-palmas-island|title=Special Report: The legal battle for Palmas island (conclusion)|date=February 3, 2003|newspaper=The Philippine Star}}</ref>\n\n===Judiciary===\nProvisional Law on the Judiciary was issued on March 7, 1899, in accordance to the provisions of the 1899 Malolos Constitution providing that the Chief Justice shall be chosen by the National Assembly with the concurrence of the president and secretaries of the government. Aguinaldo appointed [[Apolinario Mabini]] to be the [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines]] on August 23, 1899; however, the appointment did not materialize because of the Philippine\u2013American War.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pobre|first=Cesar|title=Philippine Legislature}}</ref><ref>[http://opinion.inquirer.net/19225/blocked-from-being-chief-justice Blocked from being chief justice]</ref><ref>[http://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/about/gov/judiciary/sc/ History of the Supreme Court]</ref>\n\n==Finances==\n[[File:Stamps first 1898-99 Stamps FILIPINO.jpg|thumb|The postage stamps of the Revolutionary Government.]]\n[[File:Un Peso Republica Filipina.jpg|thumb|The one [[Philippine peso|peso]] of the Revolutionary Government.]]\n\nOne of the important laws passed by the Malolos Congress was the law providing for a national loan to buoy the national budget in which the Republic was trying to balance. The loan, worth 20 million pesos, was to be paid in 40 years with an annual interest of six percent. The law was decreed by Aguinaldo on November 30, 1898.<ref name=\"malolos crisis\"/>{{clarify|date=January 2014<!-- was such a loan ever made? ... etc. See e.g., https://books.google.com/books?id=TN4MAQAAMAAJ&q=%22national+loan%22+philippines+%22twenty+million%22&dq=%22national+loan%22+philippines+%22twenty+million%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=05rnUsH4KsWUiAf7s4E4&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA I've never seen either this book or the book cited, and don't know what details they might provide -->}}{{page needed|date=February 2015<!--I have a copy of the book but don't know where to look in it to try to confirm this assertion-->}}\n\n==Military==\nWhen Philippine independence was declared on June 12, 1898, the [[Philippine Revolutionary Army]] was renamed the Philippine Republican Army. Aguinaldo then appointed [[Antonio Luna]] as Director or Assistant Secretary of War by September 28, 1898, and the Philippines first military school, the Academia Militar was established in Malolos.\n\nWhen the Republic was inaugurated on January 23, Luna had succeeded [[Artemio Ricarte]] as the Commanding General of the Republican Army. With such powers at hand, Luna attempted to transform the weak, undisciplined revolutionary army into a disciplined regular army for the service of the Republic.<ref name=\"V.R. Jose\">{{cite book|last=Jose|first=Vicencio|title=The Rise and Fall of Antonio Luna|year=1972|publisher=Solar Pub. Corporation|url=https://books.google.com/?id=SjFQPgAACAAJ|isbn=9789711707002}}</ref>\n\n==Seats of government==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2017}}\n{{Location map many\n|Luzon\n| width       = 350px\n|label1=Nueva Ecija\n    |marksize=8\n    |pos=bottom \n    |lat=15.16|long=120.54\n|label2= Pampanga\n    |marksize2=8\n    |pos2=left\n    |lat2=15.09|long2=120.35\n|label3=Malolos\n    |marksize3=8\n    |pos3=right\n    |lat3=14.5036|long3=120.4841\n|label4=Tarlac\n    |marksize4=8\n    |pos4=left\n    |lat4=15.39|long4=120.15\n|label5=Nueva Viscaya\n    |marksize5=8\n    |pos5=left\n    |lat5=16.29|long5=121.9\n|label6=Pangasinan\n    |marksize6=8\n    |pos6=top\n    |lat6=15.43|long6=120.21\n|label7=Isabela\n    |marksize7=8\n    |pos7=top\n    |lat7=17.03|long7=122.25\n|caption=Provinces that serve as [[Capital of the Philippines|capital]] of First Philippine Republic designated by Aguinaldo in his attempt to escape the American forces\n}}\n\n===Malolos, the Official Capital of the First Philippine Republic===\n[[File:Malolos basilica.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|The Malolos Cathedral Basilica. The ''Palacio Presidencia'' and Office of the President [[Emilio Aguinaldo]] from September 1898 - March 1899.]]\n\nIn September 1898, General Emilio Aguinaldo made the Paroquia dela Inmaculada Concepcion, an Augustinian-built town church (now Cathedral Basilica) of Malolos, the executive palace while the nearby Barasoain Church served as the legislative house where the Malolos Constitution was written. When the Americans captured Malolos, Aguinaldo ordered General Antonio Luna to burn the Malolos Church, including its huge silver altar.\n\n[[File:Sidecohousejf2.JPG|thumb|left|Sideco house served as Emilio Aguinaldo's capitol from the fall of Malolos on March 31, 1899, until May 17, 1899, when San Isidro was taken by the Americans.]]\n\n===Sideco house (Emilio Aguinaldo's Office at Nueva Ecija)===\nThe house became the seat of General Emilio Aguinaldo's First Philippine Republic when he established it as his headquarters in San Isidro during the last part of his odyssey from the American forces.\n\nOn the 29th of March 1899, Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo arrived in San Isidro, Nueva Ecija and the town was made temporary capital of the First Philippine Republic. He stayed in this house which served as his executive office. When the Americans occupied San Isidro, the Sideco house served as the headquarters of Col. [[Frederick Funston]] who would later capture General Aguinaldo in Palanan, Isabela. General Aguinaldo's capture is said to have been planned in this house. It is now occupied by a Christian organization.<ref name=captureofaguinaldo1901>[http://philippineamericanwar.webs.com/captureofaguinaldo1901.htm Capture of Aguinaldo, March 23, 1901], Philippine-American War, 1899-1902 by Arnaldo Dumindin</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of the Philippines (1898-1946)]]\n*[[Malolos Constitution]]\n*[[Sovereignty of the Philippines]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Agoncillo|first=Teodoro A. |title=Malolos: The Crisis of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LnxvAAAACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=University of the Philippines Press|isbn=978-971-542-096-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Calit|first=Harry S. |title=The Philippines: current issues and historical background|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWtyAAAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Nova Science Publishers|isbn=978-1-59033-576-5|ref=harv}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Duka|first=C.|title=Struggle for Freedom' 2008 Ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4wk8yqCEmJUC|year=2008|publisher=Rex Bookstore, Inc.|isbn=978-971-23-5045-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Guevara|1972}} |reference=Guevara, Sulpico ed. 1972. [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=philamer;iel=1;view=toc;idno=aab1246.0001.001 The Laws of the First Philippine Republic (The Laws of Malalos)]. National Historical Institute, Manila.}}, (published online 2005, University of Michigan Library)\n* {{cite book |last=Halstead |first=Murat |url=https://archive.org/details/storyphilippine00halsgoog |title=The Story of the Philippines and Our New Possessions, Including the Ladrones, Hawaii, Cuba and Porto Rico |year=1898 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kalaw |first=Maximo Manguiat |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=afj2233.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=17 |title=The Development of Philippine Politics |publisher=Oriental commercial |year=1927 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Linn|first=Brian McAllister |authorlink=Brian McAllister Linn |title=The Philippine War, 1899-1902|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PSJGPgAACAAJ |year=2000a|publisher=University Press of Kansas|isbn=978-0-7006-1225-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Linn|first=Brian McAllister |title=The U.S. Army and Counterinsurgency in the Philippine War, 1899-1902|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-5WOrmt_VxcC|year=2000b|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-0-8078-4948-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schultz|first=Jeffrey D. |title=Encyclopedia of Minorities in American Politics: African Americans and Asian Americans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WDV40aK1T-sC|year=2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-57356-148-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Titherington |first=Richard Handfield |title=A history of the Spanish\u2013American War of 1898\n|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishamwar00tithrich |year=1900 |publisher=D. Appleton and Company |ref=harv}} (republished by [https://openlibrary.org/ openlibrary.org])\n* {{cite book|last=Zafra|first=Nicolas |title=Philippine history through selected sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g1MeAAAAMAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Alemar-Phoenix Pub. House|ref=harv}}\n* [http://www.msc.edu.ph/centennial/republic.html The Malolos Republic]\n* [http://www.univie.ac.at/Voelkerkunde/apsis/aufi/pop/malolos.htm The First Philippine Republic at Malolos]\n* [http://www.thecorpusjuris.com/constitutions/1899-constitution.php The 1899 Malolos Constitution (includes original Spanish version)]\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/catalog/world/readfile?fk_files=168478 Project Gutenberg - Panukala sa Pagkakana nang Rep\u00fablika nang Pilipinas by Apolinario Mabini]\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Philippine Revolution}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philippine Republic, First}}\n[[Category:First Philippine Republic| ]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Philippine history|First Philippine Republic]]\n[[Category:Former republics]]\n[[Category:Former unrecognized countries]]\n[[Category:Philippine\u2013American War|First Philippine Republic]]\n[[Category:Philippine Revolution|First Philippine Republic]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1899]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1901]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Self-proclaimed independent republic from 1899\u20131901}}\n{{Infobox country\n| native_name            = ''Rep\u00fablica Filipina''<br />''Rep\u00fablik\u00e1ng Pilipino''\n| conventional_long_name = Philippine Republic\n| common_name            = the Philippines\n| year_start             = 1899<ref name=clarifydates group=Note>The Malolos Constitution was approved by the [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|Malolos Congress]] on January 20, 1899, sanctioned by [[Emilio Aguinaldo|Aguinaldo]] on January 21, and promulgated on January 22 (see items [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/106?page=root;size=100;view=image 27] and [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/123?page=root;size=100;view=image 27a] in {{Harvnb|Guevara|1972}}). The republic was proclaimed on 23 January (see items [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/138?view=image&size=100 28], [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/139?page=root;size=100;view=image 28a] and [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/p/philamer/aab1246.0001.001/140?page=root;size=100;view=image 28b] in {{Harvnb|Guevara|1972}}).</ref>\n| year_end               = 1901\n| date_start             = January 23,\n| date_end               = March 23,\n| event_end              = Dissolved{{ref label|dissolution|''i''|none}}\n| p1                     = Spanish East Indies\n| flag_p1                = Flag of Spain (1785-1873 and 1875-1931).svg\n| p2                     = Revolutionary Government of the Philippines (1898\u20131899){{!}}Revolutionary Government\n| flag_p2                = Philippines Aguinaldo flag (obverse).svg\n| s1                     = United States Military Government of the Philippine  Islands{{!}}Military Government of the Philippine Islands\n| flag_s1                = US flag 45 stars.svg\n| image_flag             = Philippines Aguinaldo flag (obverse).svg\n| image_coat             = Emblem of the First Philippine Republic.png\n| symbol_type            = [[Coat of arms of the Philippines|Emblem]]\n| image_map              = Map of Philippines First Republic.png\n| image_map_caption      = Territory claimed by the Philippine Republic\n| national_anthem        = ''[[Lupang Hinirang|Marcha Nacional Filipina]]''<br />{{center|[[File:Himno Nacional Filipina.ogg]] }}\n| capital                = {{bulleted list\n | {{nowrap|[[Malolos]], [[Bulacan]] (''official'')}} {{nowrap|January 23, 1899<ref name=clarifydates group=Note />}} {{nowrap|to March 29, 1899}}\n | other temporary capitals<ref name=capitals group=Note>Sources disagree regarding the specific locations which were temporarily capitals of the Philippine Republic. For example:\n | {{Harvnb|Duka|2008|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=4wk8yqCEmJUC&pg=PA191 191]}} lists a progression after Malolos from [[Cabanatuan]], [[Nueva Ecija]] to [[Tarlac City|Tarlac]] to [[Bayombong, Nueva Vizcaya]] to [[Bayambang, Pangasinan]].\n | {{Harvnb|Schultz|2000|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WDV40aK1T-sC&pg=PA322 322]}} says that the capital transferred from Malolos to [[San Fernando, Pampanga]].\n | {{Harvnb|Calit|2003|p=57}} asserts that Aguinaldo established his capital at [[San Isidro, Nueva Ecija]] after abandoning Malolos.\n | {{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=136}} does not give a comprehensive list, but notes that Aguinaldo's cabinet, reduced to a handful of ministers, moved from capital to capital.</ref>{{sup|}} }}\n| common_languages       = [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], and other [[Philippine languages]]\n| religion               = {{unbulleted list | [[Roman Catholicism]] | [[Philippine Independent Church]] }}\n| government_type        = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] constitutional republic\n| title_leader           = [[President of the Philippines|President]]\n| leader1                = [[Emilio Aguinaldo]]\n| year_leader1           = 1899\u20131901\n| leader2                = \n| year_leader2           = \n| title_deputy           = \n| deputy1                = \n| year_deputy1           = \n| deputy2                = \n| year_deputy2           = \n| legislature            = [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|La Asamblea Nacional]]\n| era                    = Philippine Revolution\n| area_km2           = 298,712 <ref name=NBE>[http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es/results.vm?o=&w=7.832.719+habitantes.&f=text&t=%2Bcreation&l=600&l=700&s=0&lang=en La Dinast\u00eda (Barcelona). 29/11/1898, page 3.] as returned in search results at the [http://hemerotecadigital.bne.es National Library of Spain].</ref>\n| stat_pop1              = 7,832,719<ref name=NBE />\n| stat_year1             = 1898\n| currency               = [[Philippine peso|Peso]]\n| footnotes              = {{Ordered list\n | list_style_type = lower-roman\n | item_style      = font-style:italic;\n | {{note label|dissolution|i|none}}For further info re-dissolution, see capture of [[Emilio Aguinaldo]].\n }}\n|status=[[List of historical unrecognized states and dependencies|Unrecognized state]]}}\n{{History of the Philippines}}\n[[File:Gen Aguinaldo.jpg|thumb|upright|First President of the Philippines, [[Emilio Aguinaldo]], in the field.]]\n[[File:Malolosrepublic.jpeg|thumb|upright=1.35|The Inauguration of the First Philippine Republic in Malolos, January 23, 1899]]\n\nThe '''Philippine Republic''' ({{lang-es|Rep\u00fablica Filipina<!-- per the official text of the 1899 constitution -->}}; {{lang-fil|Rep\u00fablik\u00e1ng Pilipino}}), more commonly known as the '''First Philippine Republic''' or the '''Malolos Republic''', was a nascent [[Philippine Revolution|revolutionary government]] in the [[Philippines]]. It was formally established with the proclamation of the [[Malolos Constitution]] on January 21, 1899, in [[Malolos]], [[Bulacan]],<ref name=clarifydates group=Note /> and endured until the capture of President [[Emilio Aguinaldo]] by the [[Military of the United States|American forces]] on March 23, 1901, in [[Palanan, Isabela|Palanan]], [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]], which effectively dissolved the First Republic.\n\nThe First Philippine Republic was established after the [[Philippine Revolution]] against the [[Spanish Empire]] (1896-1897) and the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] between Spain and the [[United States]] (1898). Following the American victory at the [[Battle of Manila Bay]], Aguinaldo returned to the Philippines, issued the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]] on June 12, 1898, and established a revolutionary Philippine government. In December 1898, Spain sold the Philippines to the United States in the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|1898 Treaty of Paris]], making the United States formally the Philippines colonial power. The Malolos Constitution establishing the First Philippine Republic was proclaimed the following month. The [[Philippine\u2013American War]] began in February 1899, which the Philippine Republic lost.\n\nThe Philippine Republic was the first constitutional republic in Asia.<ref name=guevara2005pp104-119>{{cite book\n|editor-last=Guevara|editor-first=Sulpico|title=The Laws of the First Philippine Republic (the laws of Malolos) 1898\u20131899 |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=philamer;iel=1;view=toc;idno=aab1246.0001.001\n|location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|publisher=University of Michigan Library|publication-date=1972|year=2005\n|pages=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer;cc=philamer;rgn=full%20text;idno=aab1246.0001.001;didno=aab1246.0001.001;view=image;seq=00000122 104\u2013119]|accessdate=2008-03-26|ref=harv}}. (English translation by Sulpicio Guevara)</ref> Although there were several Asian republics predating the First Philippine Republic for example, the [[Mahajanapadas]] of ancient India, the [[Lanfang Republic]], the [[Republic of Formosa]] or the [[Republic of Ezo]], the Republic at Malolos was the first to frame a comprehensive constitution duly approved by a partially elected congress.<ref name=\"tucker2009p364\">{{cite book|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C. |title=The Encyclopedia of the Spanish\u2013American and Philippine\u2013American Wars: A Political, Social, and Military History|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8V3vZxOmHssC|year=2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-951-1|page=[http://books.google.com.ph/books?id=8V3vZxOmHssC&pg=RA1-PA364 364]|ref=harv}}</ref>{{fv|date=August 2019|reason=no support for either the assertion re the other listed asian republics or the assertion reading, \"the Republic at Malolos was the first to frame a comprehensive constitution duly approved by a partially elected congress\"}}\n\n==History==\nIn 1896, the Philippine Revolution began against Spanish colonial rule. In 1897, Philippine forces led by Aguinaldo signed a ceasefire with the Spanish authorities and Aguinaldo and other leaders went into exile in Hong Kong.  In April 1898, the Spanish\u2013American War broke out.  The U.S. Navy's Asiatic Squadron, then in Hong Kong, sailed to the Philippines to engage the Spanish naval forces. On May 1, 1898, the U.S. Navy decisively defeated the Spanish Navy in the [[Battle of Manila Bay]]. Later in May, Aguinaldo returned to the Philippines, established a dictatorial government on May 24, 1898<ref name=\"423\u2013427\">{{Harvnb|Kalaw|1927|pp=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=afj2233.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=443 423\u2013427]}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Titherington|1900|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/spanishamwar00tithrich#page/357/mode/2up 357\u2013358]}}</ref> (formally established by decree on June 18<ref>{{Harvnb|Guevara|1972|pp=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=28 10\u201312]}}</ref>), and on June 12, 1898, at Aguinaldo's ancestral home in Cavite, issued the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]] from Spain.  Following the proclamation of independence Aguinaldo established a revolutionary government on June 23, 1898, under which the partly-elected and partly-appointed [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines|Malolos Congress]] convened on 15 September to write a constitution.<ref name=constitution>{{Harvnb|Guevara|1972|pp=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=122&size=100 104\u2013119]}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 1898, the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|1898 Treaty of Paris]] was signed, ending the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] and transferring the Philippines from Spain to the United States.<ref name=TofP>{{citation|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/19th_century/sp1898.asp|title=Treaty of Peace Between the United States and Spain; December 10, 1898|publisher=[[Yale]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Malolos Constitution]] written by the congress was proclaimed on 22 January 1899, creating what is known today as the First Philippine Republic, with Aguinaldo as its president.<ref name=\"quod.lib.umich.edu\">{{Harvnb|Guevara|1972|p=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=122&size=100 104]}}</ref><ref name=\"423\u2013427\"/> The constitution was approved by delegates to the Malolos Congress on January 20, 1899, and sanctioned by Aguinaldo the next day.<ref name=\"quod.lib.umich.edu\"/> The convention had earlier elected Aguinaldo president on January 1, 1899, leading to his inauguration on January 23. Parts of the constitution gave Aguinaldo the power to [[rule by decree]].{{refn|The three parts of the constitution which are of particular interest are:\n:*Article 4, which lists three distinct powers, \"the legislative, the executive, and the judicial\", specifies that any two or more of these powers shall never be vested in a single individual, and specifies that the legislative power shall never be vested in a single individual.<ref name=constitution />\n:*Title VI, comprising articles 54 and 55, which mandate the election of seven legislators to a Permanent Commission which is to meet when convoked by its presiding officer during periods of legislative adjournment. This commission is mandated, among other things, \"To act on pending matters which require proper action.\"<ref name=constitution />\n:*Article 99, which read, \"Notwithstanding the general rule established in paragraph 2 of Article 4, in the meantime that the country is fighting for its independence, the Government is empowered to resolve during the closure of the Congress all questions and difficulties not provided for in the laws, which give rise to unforeseen events, by the issuance of decrees, of which the Permanent Commission shall be duly apprised as well as the Assembly when it meets in accordance with this Constitution.\"<ref name=constitution />\n:In April 1899, the Permanent Commission is said to have been composed of Pedro A. Paterno, Felix Ferrer, Juan Nepomuceno, Arsenic Cruz Herrera, Joaquin Gonzales, Hugo Ilagan, and Alberto Barretto.<ref>{{Harvnb|Zafra|1967|p=[https://books.google.com/books?ei=SkGaTpm1DO\u2013UiQeU3aSsAg&ct=result&id=g1MeAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22permanent+commission%22+philippines&q=%22Pedro+A.+Paterno%2C+Felix+Ferrer%22#search_anchor 239]}}</ref>|group=Note}}  The constitution was titled \"Constituci\u00f3n pol\u00edtica\", and was written in Spanish.<ref name=guevara2005p88>{{Harvnb|Guevara|2005|p=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=106&size=100 88]}}</ref><ref name=guevera2005p104>{{Harvnb|Guevara|2005|p=[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=aab1246.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=122&size=100 104]}}</ref><ref name=\"tucker2009pp364-365\">{{Harvnb|Tucker|2009|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8V3vZxOmHssC&pg=RA1-PA364 364\u2013365]}}</ref>\n\n===Philippine\u2013American War===\n{{main|Philippine\u2013American War}}\n\nWhen the First Philippine Republic was constituted on January 22, 1899 in Malolos, that municipality became the seat of government of the Philippine Republic, and was serving as such when hostilities erupted between U.S. and Filipino forces in the Second Battle of Manila on February 4.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=373}}</ref> On February 4, 1899, armed conflict erupted in [[Manila]] between Philippine Republic forces and American forces occupying the city subsequent to the conclusion of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]].<ref name=linn2000app46>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=46}}</ref> That day President Aguinaldo issued a proclamation ordering and commanding that \"peace and friendly relations with the Americans be broken and that the latter be treated as enemies,  within the limits prescribed by the laws of war.\"<ref>{{Harvnb|Halstead|1898|p=[http://www.gutenberg.org/catalog/world/readfile?fk_files=58428&pageno=318 318]}}</ref> The fighting quickly escalated into the [[Battle of Manila (1899)|Second Battle of Manila]], with Philippine Republic forces being driven out of the city.<ref name=linn2000app46-49>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|pp=46\u201349}}</ref>\n\nAmerican forces pushing north from Manila after the outbreak of fighting captured [[Caloocan]] on February 10.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=379\u2013381}}</ref> On March 29, as American forces threatened Malolos, the seat of government moved to San Isidro, Nueva Ecija.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=388}}</ref> On March 31, American forces captured Malolos, the initial seat of the Philippine Republic government, which had been gutted by fires set by withdrawing Philippine Republic forces.<ref name=linn2000ap99>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=99}}</ref> Emilio Aguinaldo and the core of the revolutionary government had by then moved to [[San Isidro, Nueva Ecija]].<ref name=linn2000ap109>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=109}}</ref> Peace negotiations with the American [[Schurman Commission]] during a brief ceasefire in April\u2013May 1899 failed,<ref name=linn2000ap109 /> and San Isidro fell to American forces on May 16.<ref name=linn2000p116>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=116}}.</ref> The Philippine Republic core government had moved by then to [[Bamban, Tarlac]], and subsequently moved to [[Tarlac City|Tarlac town]].<ref name=linn2000app115-116>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|pp=115\u2013116}}</ref> Aguinaldo's party had already left Tarlac, the last capital of the Philippine Republic, by the time American troops occupied it on November{{nbsp}}13.<ref name=linn2000bp16>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000b|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-5WOrmt_VxcC&pg=PA16 16]}}</ref>\n\nAmerican forces captured [[Calumpit, Bulacan]] on April 27 and, moving north, captured [[Apalit, Pampanga]] with little opposition on May 4 and [[San Fernando, Pampanga]] on May 5. This forced the seat of government to be shifted according to the demands of the military situation.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=392}}</ref><ref name=capitals group=Note />\n\nIn October 1899 American forces were in [[San Fernando, Pampanga]] and the Philippine Republic was headquartered not far north of there, in [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles]]. On October 12, an American offensive to the north forced the Philippine Republic to relocate its headquarters in November to Tarlac, and then to [[Bayombong, Nueva Vizcaya]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=446}}</ref> On November 13, under pressure by American forces, Aguinaldo and a party departed Bayombong by rail for [[Calasiao, Pangasinan]], from where they immediately proceeded eastwards to Sta. Barbara in order to evade pursuing American forces. In Sta. Barbara, they joined a force of some 1200 armed men led by General [[Gregorio del Pilar]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=447}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, in a conference in [[Bayambang, Pangasinan]], Aguinaldo decided to disperse his army and begin [[guerrilla war]]. From that point on, distance and the localistic nature of the fighting prevented him from exercising a strong influence on revolutionary or military operations.<ref name=linn2000bp16 /> Recognizing that American troops blocked his escape east, he turned north and west on 15 November, crossing the mountains into [[La Union]] province.<ref>{{Harvnb|Linn|2000a|p=148}}.</ref> Aguinaldo's party eluded pursuing American forces, passing through Tirad Pass near [[Sagada, Mountain Province]] where the [[Battle of Tirad Pass]] was fought on December 2 as a [[rear guard]] action to delay the American advance and ensure his escape. At the time of the battle, Aguinaldo and his party were encamped in [[Cervantes, Ilocos Sur|Cervantes]], about 10&nbsp;km south of the pass. After being notified by a rider of the outcome of the battle and the death of del Pilar, Aguinaldo ordered that camp be broken, and departed with his party for Cayan settlement.<ref>{{cite book|author=Teodoro A. Agoncillo|title=Malolos: The Crisis of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LnxvAAAACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=University of the Philippines Press|isbn=978-971-542-096-9|page=454}}</ref> Aguinaldo was captured by American forces on March 23, 1901 in [[Palanan, Isabela]]. Following his capture, Aguinaldo announced allegiance to the United States on April 1, 1901, formally ending the First Republic and recognizing the [[United States Military Government of the Philippine Islands|sovereignty of the United States over the Philippines]].\n\nAguinaldo's party, traveling with del Pilar's force, reached [[Manaoag, Pangasinan]] on November 15. There, the force was split into [[Vanguard (military formation)|vanguard]] and rear guard elements, with Aguinaldo and del Pilar in the vanguard.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=447\u2013448}}</ref> The vanguard force overnighted in [[Tubao, La Union]], departed there on November 16, and was in [[Naguilian, La Union]] by November 19, where word was received that American forces had taken [[Santo Tomas, La Union|Santo Tomas]] and had proceeded to [[Aringay, La Union|Aringay]]. Aguinaldo's force arrived in [[Balaoan, La Union]] on November 19, pushed on the next day, and arrived at the Tirad Pass, a natural [[choke point]], on November 23. General del Pilar decided to place a blocking force in Tirad Pass to delay pursuing American forces while Aguinaldo's party moved on.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=449}}</ref>\n\nThe Battle of Tirad Pass took place on December 2, 1899. 52 men of del Pilar's 60-man force were killed, including del Pilar himself. However, the Filipinos under del Pilar held off the Americans long enough for Aguinaldo's party to escape. Aguinaldo, encamped with his party about 10&nbsp;km south of the pass in [[Cervantes, Ilocos Sur]], was apprised of the result of the battle by a rider, and moved on. The party reached Banane settlement on December 7, where Aguinaldo paused to consider plans for the future. On December 16, the party departed for [[Abra (province)|Abra]] to join forces with General [[Manuel Tinio]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=455}}</ref> The party traveled on foot through a pass at the summit of [[Mount Polis]], and arrived at Ambayuan the next morning. The party pushed on to Banane, pursued closely by American forces. At this point, Aguinaldo's party consisted of one field officer, 11 line officers, and 107 men. The remainder of December 1899 was spent in continuous trek.<ref>{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=456\u2013458}}</ref>\n\nThe party was at the border of Abra and [[Cagayan]] provinces on Aguinaldo's 31st birthday on March 23, 1900. The trek from place to place continued until about May 22, 1900, when Aguinaldo established a new headquarters in Tierra Virgen.<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 460\">{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|p=460}}</ref> On August 27, 1900, after American forces landed at [[Aparri, Cagayan]], Aguinaldo concluded that Tierra Virgan had become untenable as a headquarters and decided to march to [[Palanan, Isabela]].<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 460\" /> On December 6, 1900, the party reached Dumasari, and arrived in Palanan the following morning.<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 485\u2013486\">{{Harvnb|Agoncillo|1997|pp=485\u2013486}}</ref> Aguinaldo remained in Palanan until his capture there by American forces with the aid of the native scouts on March 23, 1901.<ref name=\"Agoncillo 1997 485\u2013486\" />\n\n==Organization==\n===National cabinet===\nArticle 73 of the constitution established a Council of Government (Cabinet), composed of a President and seven Secretaries. The following individuals were appointed to Cabinet positions:{{refn|Details of the composition of the cabinet differ between sources. ''Master List of Cabinet Members since 1899'' in the Philippine Government's [[Official Gazette (Philippines)|Official Gazette]] is more comprehensive than other sources seen, listing information for both the Mabini and Paterno cabinets.<ref name=guevara2005p115 />}}\n\n{{Philippine cabinet|year=1899}}\n\n===Provincial and local government===\nMunicipal and provincial governments under the Republic had quickly reorganized upon Aguinaldo's decrees of June 18 and 20, 1898.<ref name=\"malolos crisis\">{{cite book|last=Agoncillo|first=Teodoro|title=Malolos: The Crisis of the Republic|year=1960}}</ref> The [[Malolos Constitution]] cited on Article 82 the organization of provincial and popular assemblies which had the power of taxation.\n\nThe government also claimed jurisdiction over the overseas territory of Palaos (Modern day Palau) and the [[Sulu archipelago]]. Both areas are represented in the Congress by representatives appointed by President Emilio Aguinaldo. Aguinaldo sent a letter to the Sultan of Sulu requesting that the islands be part of the First Philippine Republic, but the letter was ignored.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greater Philippines: Captaincy General of the Philippines|url=http://malacanang.gov.ph/7824-evolution-of-the-revolution/|website=Presidential Museum and Library|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in 2003 that Philippine congressman [[Harry Roque]] argued that Spain could not have legally ceded Palmas or any part of the Philippines to the United States because Filipinos had already established the Republic of the Philippines on June 12, 1898 before the Treaty of Paris was signed on Dec. 10, 1898.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/193954/special-report-legal-battle-palmas-island|title=Special Report: The legal battle for Palmas island (conclusion)|date=February 3, 2003|newspaper=The Philippine Star}}</ref>\n\n===Judiciary===\nProvisional Law on the Judiciary was issued on March 7, 1899, in accordance to the provisions of the 1899 Malolos Constitution providing that the Chief Justice shall be chosen by the National Assembly with the concurrence of the president and secretaries of the government. Aguinaldo appointed [[Apolinario Mabini]] to be the [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines]] on August 23, 1899; however, the appointment did not materialize because of the Philippine\u2013American War.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pobre|first=Cesar|title=Philippine Legislature}}</ref><ref>[http://opinion.inquirer.net/19225/blocked-from-being-chief-justice Blocked from being chief justice]</ref><ref>[http://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/about/gov/judiciary/sc/ History of the Supreme Court]</ref>\n\n==Finances==\n[[File:Stamps first 1898-99 Stamps FILIPINO.jpg|thumb|The postage stamps of the Revolutionary Government.]]\n[[File:Un Peso Republica Filipina.jpg|thumb|The one [[Philippine peso|peso]] of the Revolutionary Government.]]\n\nOne of the important laws passed by the Malolos Congress was the law providing for a national loan to buoy the national budget in which the Republic was trying to balance. The loan, worth 20 million pesos, was to be paid in 40 years with an annual interest of six percent. The law was decreed by Aguinaldo on November 30, 1898.<ref name=\"malolos crisis\"/>{{clarify|date=January 2014<!-- was such a loan ever made? ... etc. See e.g., https://books.google.com/books?id=TN4MAQAAMAAJ&q=%22national+loan%22+philippines+%22twenty+million%22&dq=%22national+loan%22+philippines+%22twenty+million%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=05rnUsH4KsWUiAf7s4E4&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA I've never seen either this book or the book cited, and don't know what details they might provide -->}}{{page needed|date=February 2015<!--I have a copy of the book but don't know where to look in it to try to confirm this assertion-->}}\n\n==Military==\nWhen Philippine independence was declared on June 12, 1898, the [[Philippine Revolutionary Army]] was renamed the Philippine Republican Army. Aguinaldo then appointed [[Antonio Luna]] as Director or Assistant Secretary of War by September 28, 1898, and the Philippines first military school, the Academia Militar was established in Malolos.\n\nWhen the Republic was inaugurated on January 23, Luna had succeeded [[Artemio Ricarte]] as the Commanding General of the Republican Army. With such powers at hand, Luna attempted to transform the weak, undisciplined revolutionary army into a disciplined regular army for the service of the Republic.<ref name=\"V.R. Jose\">{{cite book|last=Jose|first=Vicencio|title=The Rise and Fall of Antonio Luna|year=1972|publisher=Solar Pub. Corporation|url=https://books.google.com/?id=SjFQPgAACAAJ|isbn=9789711707002}}</ref>\n\n==Seats of government==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2017}}\n{{Location map many\n|Luzon\n| width       = 350px\n|label1=Nueva Ecija\n    |marksize=8\n    |pos=bottom \n    |lat=15.16|long=120.54\n|label2= Pampanga\n    |marksize2=8\n    |pos2=left\n    |lat2=15.09|long2=120.35\n|label3=Malolos\n    |marksize3=8\n    |pos3=right\n    |lat3=14.5036|long3=120.4841\n|label4=Tarlac\n    |marksize4=8\n    |pos4=left\n    |lat4=15.39|long4=120.15\n|label5=Nueva Viscaya\n    |marksize5=8\n    |pos5=left\n    |lat5=16.29|long5=121.9\n|label6=Pangasinan\n    |marksize6=8\n    |pos6=top\n    |lat6=15.43|long6=120.21\n|label7=Isabela\n    |marksize7=8\n    |pos7=top\n    |lat7=17.03|long7=122.25\n|caption=Provinces that serve as [[Capital of the Philippines|capital]] of First Philippine Republic designated by Aguinaldo in his attempt to escape the American forces\n}}\n\n===Malolos, the Official Capital of the First Philippine Republic===\n[[File:Malolos basilica.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|The Malolos Cathedral Basilica. The ''Palacio Presidencia'' and Office of the President [[Emilio Aguinaldo]] from September 1898 - March 1899.]]\n\nIn September 1898, General Emilio Aguinaldo made the Paroquia dela Inmaculada Concepcion, an Augustinian-built town church (now Cathedral Basilica) of Malolos, the executive palace while the nearby Barasoain Church served as the legislative house where the Malolos Constitution was written. When the Americans captured Malolos, Aguinaldo ordered General Antonio Luna to burn the Malolos Church, including its huge silver altar.\n\n[[File:Sidecohousejf2.JPG|thumb|left|Sideco house served as Emilio Aguinaldo's capitol from the fall of Malolos on March 31, 1899, until May 17, 1899, when San Isidro was taken by the Americans.]]\n\n===Sideco house (Emilio Aguinaldo's Office at Nueva Ecija)===\nThe house became the seat of General Emilio Aguinaldo's First Philippine Republic when he established it as his headquarters in San Isidro during the last part of his odyssey from the American forces.\n\nOn the 29th of March 1899, Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo arrived in San Isidro, Nueva Ecija and the town was made temporary capital of the First Philippine Republic. He stayed in this house which served as his executive office. When the Americans occupied San Isidro, the Sideco house served as the headquarters of Col. [[Frederick Funston]] who would later capture General Aguinaldo in Palanan, Isabela. General Aguinaldo's capture is said to have been planned in this house. It is now occupied by a Christian organization.<ref name=captureofaguinaldo1901>[http://philippineamericanwar.webs.com/captureofaguinaldo1901.htm Capture of Aguinaldo, March 23, 1901], Philippine-American War, 1899-1902 by Arnaldo Dumindin</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of the Philippines (1898-1946)]]\n*[[Malolos Constitution]]\n*[[Sovereignty of the Philippines]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Agoncillo|first=Teodoro A. |title=Malolos: The Crisis of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LnxvAAAACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=University of the Philippines Press|isbn=978-971-542-096-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Calit|first=Harry S. |title=The Philippines: current issues and historical background|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWtyAAAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Nova Science Publishers|isbn=978-1-59033-576-5|ref=harv}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Duka|first=C.|title=Struggle for Freedom' 2008 Ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4wk8yqCEmJUC|year=2008|publisher=Rex Bookstore, Inc.|isbn=978-971-23-5045-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Guevara|1972}} |reference=Guevara, Sulpico ed. 1972. [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=philamer;iel=1;view=toc;idno=aab1246.0001.001 The Laws of the First Philippine Republic (The Laws of Malalos)]. National Historical Institute, Manila.}}, (published online 2005, University of Michigan Library)\n* {{cite book |last=Halstead |first=Murat |url=https://archive.org/details/storyphilippine00halsgoog |title=The Story of the Philippines and Our New Possessions, Including the Ladrones, Hawaii, Cuba and Porto Rico |year=1898 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Kalaw |first=Maximo Manguiat |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=philamer&cc=philamer&idno=afj2233.0001.001&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=17 |title=The Development of Philippine Politics |publisher=Oriental commercial |year=1927 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Linn|first=Brian McAllister |authorlink=Brian McAllister Linn |title=The Philippine War, 1899-1902|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PSJGPgAACAAJ |year=2000a|publisher=University Press of Kansas|isbn=978-0-7006-1225-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Linn|first=Brian McAllister |title=The U.S. Army and Counterinsurgency in the Philippine War, 1899-1902|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-5WOrmt_VxcC|year=2000b|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-0-8078-4948-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schultz|first=Jeffrey D. |title=Encyclopedia of Minorities in American Politics: African Americans and Asian Americans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WDV40aK1T-sC|year=2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-57356-148-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Titherington |first=Richard Handfield |title=A history of the Spanish\u2013American War of 1898\n|url=https://archive.org/details/spanishamwar00tithrich |year=1900 |publisher=D. Appleton and Company |ref=harv}} (republished by [https://openlibrary.org/ openlibrary.org])\n* {{cite book|last=Zafra|first=Nicolas |title=Philippine history through selected sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g1MeAAAAMAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Alemar-Phoenix Pub. House|ref=harv}}\n* [http://www.msc.edu.ph/centennial/republic.html The Malolos Republic]\n* [http://www.univie.ac.at/Voelkerkunde/apsis/aufi/pop/malolos.htm The First Philippine Republic at Malolos]\n* [http://www.thecorpusjuris.com/constitutions/1899-constitution.php The 1899 Malolos Constitution (includes original Spanish version)]\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/catalog/world/readfile?fk_files=168478 Project Gutenberg - Panukala sa Pagkakana nang Rep\u00fablika nang Pilipinas by Apolinario Mabini]\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Philippine Revolution}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philippine Republic, First}}\n[[Category:First Philippine Republic| ]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Philippine history|First Philippine Republic]]\n[[Category:Former republics]]\n[[Category:Former unrecognized countries]]\n[[Category:Philippine\u2013American War|First Philippine Republic]]\n[[Category:Philippine Revolution|First Philippine Republic]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1899]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1901]]\n", "name_user": "2402:b801:285f:3a00:f8bd:458e:80cb:41e7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Philippine_Republic"}
{"title_page": "Al-Buraq Mosque", "text_new": "[[File:Entrance-to-Masjid-Buraq.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the al-Buraq Mosque from the western colonnade]]\n'''Al-Buraq Mosque''' ([[Arabic]]: <big>\u0645\u064e\u0633\u0652\u062c\u0650\u062f\u064f \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0628\u064f\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0642</big> - ''Masjid al-Buraq'') is a subterranean mosque next to Al-Buraq Wall, located in the Masjid al-Aqsa in the Old City of Jerusalem. This mosque is called Al-Buraq Mosque because of a ring that is nailed to its wall where Muslims believe Prophet Mohammad (peace be upon him) tied his Al-Buraq carried him from al-Masjid al-Haram to al-Masjid al-Aqsa during the Night Journey of \u201cAl-Isra\u2019 wa Al-Mi\u2019raj.\u201d <ref>{{cite book |title=Al-Aqsa Mosque Al-Haram Ash-Sharif |date=2013 |publisher=Palestine Acedemic Society for the Study of International Affairs and TIKA |location=Jerusalem |pages=22}}</ref> Today it is located inside the vaulted passage that once led to Bab Hittah (Gate of Forgiveness) or Barclay's Gate, which is at the south end of the Buraq Wall. The inside of Bab Hittah (or Barclay\u2019s Gate) which served as an entrance to al-Aqsa Mosque during the early Islamic period is currently known as al-Buraq Mosque. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Al-Ratrout |first1=Haithem Fathi |title=The architectural development of al-Aqsa Mosque in Islamic Jerusalem in the early Islamic period: sacred architecture in the shape of the 'Holy' |date=2004 |publisher=Al-Maktoum Institute Academic Press |location=Dundee |isbn=978-1-904436-03-4 |pages=340}}</ref> From an archaeological point of view, this gate must have been in use during the Umayyad period. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Al-Ratrout |first1=Haithem Fathi |title=The architectural development of al-Aqsa Mosque in Islamic Jerusalem in the early Islamic period: sacred architecture in the shape of the 'Holy' |date=2004 |publisher=Al-Maktoum Institute Academic Press |location=Dundee |isbn=978-1-904436-03-4 |pages=347}}</ref>  The entrance to the underground structure faces north in the immediately left of the Bab al-Magharibah.\n\nDue to the bilateral relations of Al-Buraq Mosque and Bab Hittah or Barclay's Gate transformed to the masjid, the historical background of one of them can give an approximate way to identify the other. According to Barclay and his followers\u2019 archeological researches especially on the gate, the height and the width of the gate are known, which can also give an opinion about the masjid. The gate measuring 5.06 metres in width and 8.80 metres in height of the doorway <ref>{{cite book |last1=Al-Ratrout |first1=Haithem Fathi |title=The architectural development of al-Aqsa Mosque in Islamic Jerusalem in the early Islamic period: sacred architecture in the shape of the 'Holy' |date=2004 |publisher=Al-Maktoum Institute Academic Press |location=Dundee |isbn=978-1-904436-03-4 |pages=339-347}}</ref>  provides insight into the dimensions of the masjid. According to archeological views; it can be concluded that this gate was used as an entrance gate to Al-Aqsa Mosque during the Umayyad period, in connection with structural features, such as the chamfered edge as a distinctive feature of all Umayyad gates leading to the enclave. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Al-Ratrout |first1=Haithem Fathi |title=The architectural development of al-Aqsa Mosque in Islamic Jerusalem in the early Islamic period: sacred architecture in the shape of the 'Holy' |date=2004 |publisher=Al-Maktoum Institute Academic Press |location=Dundee |isbn=978-1-904436-03-4 |pages=349}}</ref>\n\nOverall, the gate passage was in use until some time after 985 AD when it was blocked and changed into a cistern adjacent to Al-Buraq Mosque. (Al-Ratrout, 2004) Even though the main gate of Al-Buraq Mosque is located in Al-Aqsa\u2019s Western Wall and it is permanently sealed, the mosque is still open for prayers use another entrance located in Al-Aqsa\u2019s western corridor. <ref>{{cite book |title=Al-Aqsa Mosque Al-Haram Ash-Sharif |date=2013 |publisher=Palestine Acedemic Society for the Study of International Affairs and TIKA |location=Jerusalem |pages=22}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Buraq Wall (circled in orange).jpg|The Buraq Mosque located (circled in orange) beside the Buraq Wall (Wailing Wall/ Western Wall)\nFile:El Burak eksterior.jpg| Masjid al-Buraq, circa 1940 CE, view towards south-west\nEl Burak mosque.jpg|Vaulted space inside the subterranean chamber of Barclay's Gate, view towards east, circa 1940\nEl Burak mosque.stairs.jpg|vaulted space view towards the west, circa 1940\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Al-Buraq Mosque}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Palestine}}\n{{Old City (Jerusalem)|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buraq}}\n[[Category:Mosques in Jerusalem]]\n\n{{Asia-mosque-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Entrance-to-Masjid-Buraq.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the al-Buraq Mosque from the western colonnade]]\n'''Al-Buraq Mosque''' ([[Arabic]]: <big>\u0645\u064e\u0633\u0652\u062c\u0650\u062f\u064f \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0628\u064f\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0642</big> - ''Masjid al-Buraq'') is a subterranean mosque next to Al-Buraq Wall, located in the Masjid al-Aqsa in the Old City of Jerusalem. This mosque is called Al-Buraq Mosque because of a ring that is nailed to its wall where Muslims believe Prophet Mohammad (peace be upon him) tied his Al-Buraq carried him from al-Masjid al-Haram to al-Masjid al-Aqsa during the Night Journey of \u201cAl-Isra\u2019 wa Al-Mi\u2019raj.\u201d <ref>{{cite book |title=Al-Aqsa Mosque Al-Haram Ash-Sharif |date=2013 |publisher=Palestine Acedemic Society for the Study of International Affairs and TIKA |location=Jerusalem |pages=22}}</ref> Today it is located inside the vaulted passage that once led to Bab Hittah (Gate of Forgiveness) or Barclay's Gate, which is at the south end of the Buraq Wall. The inside of Bab Hittah (or Barclay\u2019s Gate) which served as an entrance to al-Aqsa Mosque during the early Islamic period is currently known as al-Buraq Mosque. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Al-Ratrout |first1=Haithem Fathi |title=The architectural development of al-Aqsa Mosque in Islamic Jerusalem in the early Islamic period: sacred architecture in the shape of the 'Holy' |date=2004 |publisher=Al-Maktoum Institute Academic Press |location=Dundee |isbn=978-1-904436-03-4 |pages=340}}</ref> From an archaeological point of view, this gate must have been in use during the Umayyad period. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Al-Ratrout |first1=Haithem Fathi |title=The architectural development of al-Aqsa Mosque in Islamic Jerusalem in the early Islamic period: sacred architecture in the shape of the 'Holy' |date=2004 |publisher=Al-Maktoum Institute Academic Press |location=Dundee |isbn=978-1-904436-03-4 |pages=347}}</ref>  The entrance to the underground structure faces north in the immediately left of the Bab al-Magharibah.\n\nThis small structure, near the south-west corner of the Al-Aqsa compound is believed to be the place where [[Muhammad]] tied the [[Buraq]], the winged riding animal upon which he rode during the Night of Ascension ([[Isra and Mi'raj|Isra' and Mi'raj]]), there's an iron ring in the southern wall pointing to the relation between the mosque and the al-Buraq of Muhammad, but this is only a modern installation.<ref name=\"madainburaq\"></ref><ref name=\"Gibson\" />\n\nThe mosque was described by [[Abd al-Ghani al-Nabulsi]] in 1689.<ref>{{cite book | author=Amikam Elad | year = 1999 | title = Medieval Jerusalem and Islamic Worship | publisher = Brill |pages = 101\u2013102}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Buraq Wall (circled in orange).jpg|The Buraq Mosque located (circled in orange) beside the Buraq Wall (Wailing Wall/ Western Wall)\nFile:El Burak eksterior.jpg| Masjid al-Buraq, circa 1940 CE, view towards south-west\nEl Burak mosque.jpg|Vaulted space inside the subterranean chamber of Barclay's Gate, view towards east, circa 1940\nEl Burak mosque.stairs.jpg|vaulted space view towards the west, circa 1940\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Al-Buraq Mosque}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Palestine}}\n{{Old City (Jerusalem)|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buraq}}\n[[Category:Mosques in Jerusalem]]\n\n{{Asia-mosque-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cagri Onat", "label": "safe", "comment": "some archaeologically proved features are added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Buraq_Mosque"}
